WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.680
[Amit Varma]: What goes into the making of a life? Sometimes, when we look at someone at a particular point

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:15.920
[Amit Varma]: in time, it might appear that they are who they were meant to be. This could be hindsight

00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:20.520
[Amit Varma]: bias in play. In hindsight, we see events following a linear path and everything seems

00:00:20.520 --> 00:00:25.380
[Amit Varma]: bound to happen. That's never the case. But having said that, it also may not be the case

00:00:25.380 --> 00:00:30.360
[Amit Varma]: that everything is random and anyone could be anything. We do have an essential nature,

00:00:30.360 --> 00:00:35.920
[Amit Varma]: even if that essential nature is itself accidental, and the paths we go down on conform to that.

00:00:35.920 --> 00:00:40.040
[Amit Varma]: Now, many of the episodes I've recorded in the last couple of years have been like oral

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:45.120
[Amit Varma]: histories and have an element of the memoir to them. And one common pattern I have seen

00:00:45.120 --> 00:00:49.160
[Amit Varma]: is that my guests never planned to be where they landed up. When they were young, they

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:53.440
[Amit Varma]: did not have some grand bird's eye view with which they planned their lives. Instead, they

00:00:53.440 --> 00:00:58.120
[Amit Varma]: were often locked into a moment they did something that made sense at the time, and one thing

00:00:58.120 --> 00:01:02.880
[Amit Varma]: led to another. In fact, I invite you to think about your life. Are you where you plan to

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:07.440
[Amit Varma]: be? How much of it was intentional? If you had to do things all over again, what would

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:12.080
[Amit Varma]: you change? These thoughts came to my mind because this episode features a remarkable

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:16.880
[Amit Varma]: guest with a remarkable life. And speaking to her, it's clear that she did not set out

00:01:16.880 --> 00:01:21.280
[Amit Varma]: to be remarkable to be a brave dissenter to go to prison for her beliefs. Instead, she

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:26.040
[Amit Varma]: always followed paths that interested her, that were authentic to herself, and to the

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:32.760
[Amit Varma]: moment. And then life happened. And here we are.

00:01:32.760 --> 00:01:37.960
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:37.960 --> 00:01:45.560
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:45.560 --> 00:01:49.360
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is Trishta Settleward, who most of you

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:53.520
[Amit Varma]: will know as a human rights activist who has relentlessly fought to get justice for the

00:01:53.520 --> 00:01:59.440
[Amit Varma]: victims of the 2002 riots in Gujarat. She succeeded to some extent, but the fight continues,

00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:04.360
[Amit Varma]: and she even spent some time in jail recently, persecuted by a regime that she continues

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:09.960
[Amit Varma]: to fight. But Trishta is a lot more than just a bleeding heart activist, and her activism

00:02:09.960 --> 00:02:15.360
[Amit Varma]: involves a lot more than the 2002 riots. She was born to an illustrious family of lawyers

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:19.520
[Amit Varma]: and could have followed in those footsteps and lived a plush life. She loved to write,

00:02:19.520 --> 00:02:25.840
[Amit Varma]: and she was interested in politics. Her first published letter to the editor in 1978 protested

00:02:25.840 --> 00:02:30.360
[Amit Varma]: the authoritarianism of Indira Gandhi. She joined journalism after college and was a

00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:36.680
[Amit Varma]: reporter between 1983 and 1993. In that time, she covered various kinds of communal violence

00:02:36.680 --> 00:02:40.760
[Amit Varma]: and realized that there was a deeper current in our society that mainstream media could

00:02:40.760 --> 00:02:46.080
[Amit Varma]: not cover. She formed Communalism Combat in 1993 with her partner Javed Anand, with the

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:50.920
[Amit Varma]: aim of fighting communalism from all communities. They wrote about the horror of what the Taliban

00:02:50.920 --> 00:02:55.240
[Amit Varma]: was doing in Afghanistan, about the plight of Bangladeshi Hindus. They criticized the

00:02:55.240 --> 00:03:01.480
[Amit Varma]: Jamaat-e-Islami in India. And Trishta herself wrote five important stories on what was unfolding

00:03:01.480 --> 00:03:07.800
[Amit Varma]: in Gujarat before 2002. She saw society getting increasingly fractured and warned about Gujarat

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:12.680
[Amit Varma]: exploding into criminal violence well before it happened. And when the 2002 riots took

00:03:12.680 --> 00:03:17.640
[Amit Varma]: place, she played a part in helping the victims and in fighting for justice for them. That's

00:03:17.640 --> 00:03:21.920
[Amit Varma]: a fight we know her for, but she's also fighting for other causes, such as the unseen chaos

00:03:21.920 --> 00:03:27.000
[Amit Varma]: that's unfolding in Assam over the impending Citizenship Act. She's also a fine scholar

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:31.760
[Amit Varma]: who's been teaching young students about history and politics for over two decades. In fact,

00:03:31.760 --> 00:03:37.560
[Amit Varma]: the thing that struck me most about Trishta was that she is both a thinker and a doer,

00:03:37.560 --> 00:03:41.960
[Amit Varma]: and the thinking and the doing inform each other. She's had a rich life and has tons

00:03:41.960 --> 00:03:46.400
[Amit Varma]: of insight to share on our country and our times. I loved her memoir, Foot Soldier of

00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:50.900
[Amit Varma]: the Constitution, which I recommend all of you buy. And I love this conversation. Note

00:03:50.900 --> 00:03:55.580
[Amit Varma]: by the way that we didn't discuss a few things that are sub judice, but there is still so

00:03:55.580 --> 00:04:00.560
[Amit Varma]: much here to marvel at and to learn from. Before we start though, let's take a quick

00:04:00.560 --> 00:04:04.080
[Amit Varma]: commercial break.

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:07.640
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer, but never quite gotten down to it? Well, I'd love

00:04:07.640 --> 00:04:12.320
[Amit Varma]: to help you. Since April 2020, I've taught 20 cohorts of my online course, The Art of

00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:16.760
[Amit Varma]: Clear Writing. An online community has now sprung up of all my past students. We have

00:04:16.760 --> 00:04:21.680
[Amit Varma]: workshops, a newsletter to showcase the work of students, and vibrant community interaction.

00:04:21.680 --> 00:04:26.000
[Amit Varma]: In the course itself, through four webinars spread over four weekends, I share all I know

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.200
[Amit Varma]: about the craft and practice of clear writing. There are many exercises, much interaction,

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:34.640
[Amit Varma]: a lovely and lively community at the end of it. The course costs rupees 10,000 plus GST,

00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:39.440
[Amit Varma]: or about $150, and is a monthly thing. So if you're interested, head on over to register

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:44.920
[Amit Varma]: at indiauncut.com slash clear writing. That's indiauncut.com slash clear writing. Being

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:50.200
[Amit Varma]: a good writer doesn't require God given talent, just the willingness to work hard and a clear

00:04:50.200 --> 00:04:55.880
[Amit Varma]: idea of what you need to do to refine your skills. I can help you.

00:04:55.880 --> 00:05:00.480
[Amit Varma]: Teesta, welcome to the scene in the unseen. Great to be here, Amit.

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:04.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, normally, when I'm sitting with a guest, we go a long way back and talk about

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:08.640
[Amit Varma]: their childhood and all of that. But with you, I want to go even further back. Because

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:15.400
[Amit Varma]: just now at lunch, we were talking about Maharashtra and Gujarat. And you were telling me about

00:05:15.400 --> 00:05:21.200
[Amit Varma]: how Maharashtra has so many different syncretic traditions. So it's not just the RSS strain

00:05:21.200 --> 00:05:25.640
[Amit Varma]: of a particular kind of Hindutva, which is relatively recent, like you pointed out, but

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:31.160
[Amit Varma]: it goes back centuries. And equally, you mentioned how Gujarat interestingly doesn't despite

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:37.600
[Amit Varma]: producing outliers, I guess, like Gandhi and Patel. Can you elaborate a little bit more

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:38.600
[Guest]: on this for me?

00:05:38.600 --> 00:05:43.880
[Guest]: Yeah, actually, it's a fascinating discussion in itself, because for many of us who look

00:05:43.880 --> 00:05:50.880
[Guest]: at history and Indian constitution and law, not just in books, but in practice, have found

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:58.560
[Guest]: that this subcontinent, you know, the soil, this India, South Asia, has had a very strong

00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:06.760
[Guest]: strain of resistance, if you like, of questioning of rationality, which goes back like, centuries,

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:13.720
[Guest]: centuries, it could even go back to the early Indian period, or even the certainly the early

00:06:13.720 --> 00:06:20.840
[Guest]: medieval period, early Indian as well. Because if you look at the entire question of Buddha

00:06:20.840 --> 00:06:26.400
[Guest]: Buddhism, Jainism, Buddhism, then of course, the resurgence of Shankaracharya, trying to

00:06:26.400 --> 00:06:32.480
[Guest]: bind it all back together for the Sanatan Dharma. Then you look at the early medieval

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:38.160
[Guest]: and you have the Bhakti Sufi traditions and you have, you know, across the country, and

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:44.560
[Guest]: particularly Western, Central, North India, Bengal, East India, Northeast, this entire

00:06:44.560 --> 00:06:51.720
[Guest]: business of looking at faith, spirituality, the individual, her or his space in it and

00:06:51.720 --> 00:06:57.840
[Guest]: questioning and always looking at equality and non-discrimination through it, has been

00:06:57.840 --> 00:07:02.720
[Guest]: there, has been very much there. I mean, you can name them, you can look at Basavanna in

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:11.200
[Guest]: modern day Karnataka, Narayan, Guru, more modern period, you can look at Kabir in Banaras,

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:17.960
[Guest]: you know, and we know where Banaras is today, and you look at Guru Nanak, and you look at

00:07:17.960 --> 00:07:23.040
[Guest]: coming back to your, you know, your, the Western Indian, what I'm talking about, that RSS is

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:29.000
[Guest]: a very new thing. I mean, it's a new modern proto-fascist concept. It's, before that we

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:35.920
[Guest]: had Eknath, we had Namdev, we had Tukaram, and then we've had Phuleyambedkar. So the

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:40.600
[Guest]: argument for some of us is that the inherent values of the Indian Constitution, you know,

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:45.760
[Guest]: which formally came to us with the discussions around the Karachi Resolution, which was an

00:07:45.760 --> 00:07:51.680
[Guest]: Indian National Congress in the 1930s, where Subhash Chandra Bose as president and Gandhi

00:07:51.680 --> 00:07:56.320
[Guest]: as the mentor, but it was Subhash Chandra Bose, the agricultural struggle, the workers

00:07:56.320 --> 00:08:01.520
[Guest]: struggle, the left traditions that influenced and pushed the Congress into making the plea

00:08:01.520 --> 00:08:06.320
[Guest]: for fundamental rights for all, which included workers' rights and women's rights and rights

00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:14.400
[Guest]: of all genders, etc. Those are not entirely foreign. And anyway, I'm not trying to say

00:08:14.400 --> 00:08:20.560
[Guest]: that there's anything wrong with internationalism, because we know the modern discourse that

00:08:20.560 --> 00:08:26.760
[Guest]: came with the French Revolution was also a metamorphosis across continents. But there's

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:31.520
[Guest]: a strong strain of our people, particularly people who are lesser privileged in terms

00:08:31.520 --> 00:08:39.960
[Guest]: of class and caste, questioning the rigidity of caste and of privilege. And Basavanna talked

00:08:39.960 --> 00:08:49.840
[Guest]: about gender in a very, very strong way. So, you had the Rashtra Seva Dalas worked on Maharashtrian

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:57.440
[Guest]: women saints of the Bhakti tradition, single women. And later on, we saw Nargis and Jogin

00:08:57.440 --> 00:09:04.080
[Guest]: in the middle part of the 20th century, you know, and she was representing that. It's

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:09.600
[Guest]: the Miras and the Janabais and all of that, who took to the streets singing to their God

00:09:09.600 --> 00:09:16.160
[Guest]: and said, we are not going to be living within the family, within patriarchy and within the

00:09:16.160 --> 00:09:20.640
[Guest]: bonds of marriage or whatever. And you had the Gargi and Jayabala in the Vedic period

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:25.080
[Guest]: also saying that we have a right to the Vedic scriptures. So, there has been a strong strain

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:31.480
[Guest]: of this. And all of this is also metamorphosed into the constitution as much as modern ideas

00:09:31.480 --> 00:09:38.120
[Guest]: of equality, fraternity, justice and non-discrimination. Now, between Maharashtra and Gujarat, I found

00:09:38.120 --> 00:09:42.080
[Guest]: it fascinating because I speak better Marathi than, though Gujarati is my mother tongue,

00:09:42.080 --> 00:09:47.520
[Guest]: but I speak and read better Marathi because this is my karmabhoomi, if you like, because

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:52.520
[Guest]: it's three, four generations we've lived here. But thanks to my paternal grandfather, I can

00:09:52.520 --> 00:09:58.640
[Guest]: read and speak Gujarati as well. But I've seen that in Maharashtra, with all the rigidity

00:09:58.640 --> 00:10:06.440
[Guest]: of a kind of Brahmanism and conservatism, which is evident in certain traditions, you've

00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:12.280
[Guest]: always had this subaltern questioning and that has manifested itself, manifests itself

00:10:12.280 --> 00:10:17.600
[Guest]: in reform. It manifests itself in something fascinating because I teach history in schools

00:10:17.600 --> 00:10:25.360
[Guest]: and I try to go by what Fred said, that the classroom should be the, should be the location

00:10:25.360 --> 00:10:30.840
[Guest]: for questioning and not for a one-way traffic between what you're told to be taught and

00:10:30.840 --> 00:10:37.200
[Guest]: what you're told to be learned. He said in 1848, Savitri Bai Phule and her partner opens

00:10:37.200 --> 00:10:42.680
[Guest]: the first all-girls school, possibly in the world, possibly in the world. And what is

00:10:42.680 --> 00:10:49.400
[Guest]: the, what is the concept that in one class, you like girls of different castes and communities

00:10:49.400 --> 00:10:54.400
[Guest]: studying together. Now, this is before you have the civil rights movement in the US and

00:10:54.400 --> 00:10:59.480
[Guest]: the anti-segregation civil rights movement where black girls could also come into the

00:10:59.480 --> 00:11:04.960
[Guest]: classroom. So, what does this mean? It means that there's a huge churning and an assertion

00:11:04.960 --> 00:11:13.120
[Guest]: and that I think still survives in Maharashtra with all its other regressive tendencies.

00:11:13.120 --> 00:11:18.000
[Guest]: Gujarat has been different and because of my work as first as a journalist, then as

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:22.560
[Guest]: an activist in Gujarat, I've always asked that what is this difference? Is it because

00:11:22.560 --> 00:11:29.160
[Guest]: there was no strong anti-caste movement like you see in many other parts of the country,

00:11:29.160 --> 00:11:34.080
[Guest]: particularly in Maharashtra? Of course, you had Narmad and his poetry apart from Gandhi

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:40.520
[Guest]: and Patel. Of course, you had Wali Gujarati, one of our, Wali Dakhani, one of our early

00:11:40.520 --> 00:11:44.720
[Guest]: Urdu poets coming and settling in Ahmedabad and calling Gujarati his own land. It was

00:11:44.720 --> 00:11:52.520
[Guest]: his tomb that was dug open on 28th of February 2002. But there's a mercantilism which runs

00:11:52.520 --> 00:12:01.440
[Guest]: across communities. There is a sort of prosaic non-questioning that is prevalent, you know,

00:12:01.440 --> 00:12:06.560
[Guest]: so that has affected things there. And therefore, I think for the project for the Hindu Rashtra

00:12:06.560 --> 00:12:14.600
[Guest]: and the project for the masochist authoritarian state to revile and to discredit Gandhi in

00:12:14.600 --> 00:12:22.320
[Guest]: the land of his birth, Porbandar, Gujarat was very, very important, has been very important.

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:29.560
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of strands I want to sort of follow up on. And the first is this that if we look

00:12:29.560 --> 00:12:36.200
[Amit Varma]: back through the centuries, if we look at that tradition of questioning existing structures

00:12:36.200 --> 00:12:43.360
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth, I would imagine that for most of our history, those would not be

00:12:43.360 --> 00:12:48.240
[Amit Varma]: against the state because the state would be a very distant kind of thing. It would

00:12:48.240 --> 00:12:53.600
[Amit Varma]: more be against power structures in society around you where you see caste play itself

00:12:53.600 --> 00:12:59.880
[Amit Varma]: out, or you see gender play itself out, and so on and so forth. And this sense of this

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:05.640
[Amit Varma]: strong authoritarian state, which is like a distant beast, somewhere far away, how do

00:13:05.640 --> 00:13:11.760
[Amit Varma]: you even rebel, blah, blah, blah, seems to be a relatively recent phenomenon, if we talk

00:13:11.760 --> 00:13:19.160
[Amit Varma]: in terms of centuries. Has that dimmed the fire somewhat? Because just kind of looking

00:13:19.160 --> 00:13:24.840
[Amit Varma]: back through the decades of our independence, one strand that kind of stands out is just

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:29.600
[Amit Varma]: one of apathy, one of inertia that you let things happen, you know, people almost become

00:13:29.600 --> 00:13:34.160
[Amit Varma]: fatalistic. Now, it's possible that people were always fatalistic. And, you know, it's

00:13:34.160 --> 00:13:38.240
[Amit Varma]: a bit of selection bias that we remember all the rebels and all the countercultures and

00:13:38.240 --> 00:13:43.280
[Amit Varma]: everything, and that those exist today as well. But is it that it just seems harder

00:13:43.280 --> 00:13:47.680
[Amit Varma]: to fight the distant state, which you know, you can't beat anyway. So, you know, you just

00:13:47.680 --> 00:13:49.400
[Amit Varma]: get on with things.

00:13:49.400 --> 00:13:56.560
[Guest]: You know, I think it also depends on what history we read, and which struggles we pick

00:13:56.560 --> 00:14:02.320
[Guest]: and which icons we remember. I've been fortunate through the work I've chosen to do, which

00:14:02.320 --> 00:14:07.680
[Guest]: has not become a ninth generation, high profile lawyer that I could have been because given

00:14:07.680 --> 00:14:11.880
[Guest]: the settler tradition, I could have been the ninth and you know, apart from maybe being

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:15.560
[Guest]: good at my job, I could have earned all sorts of money, but that's not the issue. The point

00:14:15.560 --> 00:14:23.360
[Guest]: is, one chose a path of, it's not about activism, it's about interrogating power structures

00:14:23.360 --> 00:14:28.160
[Guest]: at various levels. So, apart from the work I'm more known for, which is human rights

00:14:28.160 --> 00:14:34.000
[Guest]: and fighting for justice in the courts, one of my passions is education and pedagogy of

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:38.680
[Guest]: history teaching, and social science teaching in the classroom. And for that, we had this

00:14:38.680 --> 00:14:43.240
[Guest]: coach project, which we kind of undertake, and we are doing it in municipal schools and

00:14:43.240 --> 00:14:49.680
[Guest]: private schools in different parts of the country. Now, fortunately, one has been able

00:14:49.680 --> 00:14:56.280
[Guest]: to look at therefore, history and turn it on its head. And if I, answering your question,

00:14:56.280 --> 00:15:04.640
[Guest]: if I ask you that then what made the Adivasis and the agriculturalists be the first challengers

00:15:04.640 --> 00:15:10.560
[Guest]: to colonial rule, before anybody from the cities got up and found out even before Dadabhai

00:15:10.560 --> 00:15:18.720
[Guest]: Naoroji's historic pamphlet on poverty? I think, because they experienced firsthand

00:15:18.720 --> 00:15:26.280
[Guest]: what colonialism and to what extent colonial power economically and culturally debauched

00:15:26.280 --> 00:15:31.000
[Guest]: them, you know, which is not to say earlier oligarchies, coming to your question earlier

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:38.120
[Guest]: oligarchies or monarchs had an equitable relationship with them. No, there was a feudal relationship,

00:15:38.120 --> 00:15:44.760
[Guest]: they would take their share, but they left the lands alone. Okay, they left the lands

00:15:44.760 --> 00:15:52.400
[Guest]: largely alone, there was a transactional relationship, which was, of course, iniquitous, but what

00:15:52.400 --> 00:16:00.160
[Guest]: colonialism did was completely ravaged our land, our population and our people. If you

00:16:00.160 --> 00:16:06.280
[Guest]: look at Indigo, Indigo rebellion, the Santal rebellion, I mean, I mean, I've been fortunate

00:16:06.280 --> 00:16:10.920
[Guest]: enough to work with Adivasi, All India Union of Forest Working People for the last nine

00:16:10.920 --> 00:16:17.040
[Guest]: years and I have seen firsthand those struggles and how they've kept their oral histories

00:16:17.040 --> 00:16:21.640
[Guest]: alive and that has opened my eyes to the fact that we've really not looked at urban India

00:16:21.640 --> 00:16:28.240
[Guest]: and upper caste, upper class India, liberal India has not looked at these subaltern histories

00:16:28.240 --> 00:16:35.160
[Guest]: which have been manifest in challenging colonialism. I mean, that is why the land law was passed

00:16:35.160 --> 00:16:40.760
[Guest]: in 1848, that is why the forest act was passed in 1927 because the British had to clamp down

00:16:40.760 --> 00:16:48.160
[Guest]: on these struggles and if you look at the way the lawyers and the doctors and the names

00:16:48.160 --> 00:16:53.760
[Guest]: you and I know or we knew in childhood started fighting for freedom and all of them are very

00:16:53.760 --> 00:16:59.320
[Guest]: admirable, that happened like 150 years later, but these struggles had already been born

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:04.560
[Guest]: and were being challenged and they lost lives at huge cost, you know, there's Birsa Munda,

00:17:04.560 --> 00:17:11.120
[Guest]: there's named from Assam to Maharashtra to Karnataka and these are modern-day constructs,

00:17:11.120 --> 00:17:18.280
[Guest]: but to Bengal huge, Tibhaga struggle to Telangana, modern-day Telangana, Andhra Pradesh, you

00:17:18.280 --> 00:17:23.520
[Guest]: had the agriculturalists and the Adivasis challenging colonial powers like nobody else

00:17:23.520 --> 00:17:28.000
[Guest]: did, you know. So, I think that is a very important thing to remember in terms of answering

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:37.040
[Guest]: your question. I think a point will come when I think even with this fractured values that

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:42.640
[Guest]: neoliberalism has caused us where all of us are in little aspirational bubbles and it's

00:17:42.640 --> 00:17:47.680
[Guest]: not easy to collectively organize or unionize or protest anymore, traditionally protest

00:17:47.680 --> 00:17:52.240
[Guest]: anymore. I think a time will come and I just hope that human cost is not too high by then

00:17:52.240 --> 00:17:56.880
[Guest]: when people will just find what's happening is too much, just too much, even though the

00:17:56.880 --> 00:18:01.840
[Guest]: state is, it's not distant ever. The state is never distant. In fact, today the state

00:18:01.840 --> 00:18:06.680
[Guest]: appears very oppressive and very intrusive just like the colonial state was and I think

00:18:06.680 --> 00:18:11.760
[Guest]: what we are experiencing today is a kind of neo-colonialism really because if you look

00:18:11.760 --> 00:18:16.400
[Guest]: at the corporatization on the one hand and the snatching away of civil rights on the

00:18:16.400 --> 00:18:22.120
[Guest]: other and of course minority rights being right out there first, that's what we are

00:18:22.120 --> 00:18:28.080
[Guest]: seeing. So, and constitutionalism and what the freedom struggle fought for is being turned

00:18:28.080 --> 00:18:35.920
[Guest]: on its head. So, Ambedkar becomes an icon for the regime and yet the collected works

00:18:35.920 --> 00:18:42.200
[Guest]: of Ambedkar, 18 volumes are sold without the six critical volumes at the Delhi Book Fair

00:18:42.200 --> 00:18:52.320
[Guest]: which is the most and which are those caste and minorities, sorry state and minorities,

00:18:52.320 --> 00:18:57.080
[Guest]: annihilation of caste, riddles in Hinduism, the most critical books of Ambedkar when it

00:18:57.080 --> 00:19:04.880
[Guest]: comes to the Hindu religious and social structure are not part of the official volume sold by

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:09.680
[Guest]: the government of India anymore. So, you are picking and choosing, you can't ignore Ambedkar,

00:19:09.680 --> 00:19:13.720
[Guest]: you can't ignore Bhagat Singh, you can't ignore Subhash Chandra Bose. So, you pick

00:19:13.720 --> 00:19:21.800
[Guest]: and choose and you appropriate them and you try and hollow them out. The essence of these

00:19:21.800 --> 00:19:28.840
[Guest]: people was what they stood for. I mean Bhagat Singh's writing on the dangers of communalism

00:19:28.840 --> 00:19:36.840
[Guest]: of all kinds, Ambedkar's writing on not just the caste question but also on communalism

00:19:36.840 --> 00:19:42.480
[Guest]: and the state majoritarian project and why even I feel like really looking at Gandhi's

00:19:42.480 --> 00:19:46.760
[Guest]: stand on the communal award and the communal electorate because I think Ambedkar was right

00:19:46.760 --> 00:19:53.360
[Guest]: in saying that reserved constituencies should allow that section to vote for that section

00:19:53.360 --> 00:19:57.080
[Guest]: because otherwise you won't have representation of Dalits and minorities in Parliament and

00:19:57.080 --> 00:20:02.720
[Guest]: we are seeing that. So, so many issues get thrown up and I think a time will come when

00:20:02.720 --> 00:20:09.800
[Guest]: I think the apathy will be overcome by the sheer intrusion of the horror that the state

00:20:09.800 --> 00:20:11.720
[Guest]: is undertaking at the moment.

00:20:11.720 --> 00:20:16.920
[Amit Varma]: So, number of strands to go down on but it's interesting you should mention about how people

00:20:16.920 --> 00:20:21.520
[Amit Varma]: are trying to appropriate Ambedkar and Bhagat Singh and so on because we are recording this

00:20:21.520 --> 00:20:27.840
[Amit Varma]: on October 27th and just yesterday there was this announcement of you know Arvind Kejriwal

00:20:27.840 --> 00:20:33.120
[Amit Varma]: saying we must have Laxmi and Madhurga on the currency notes because our economy will

00:20:33.120 --> 00:20:37.680
[Amit Varma]: do well and on the background there were these photographs of Ambedkar and Bhagat Singh and

00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:42.360
[Amit Varma]: you know I mean what would those men have made of something like this and when I meant

00:20:42.360 --> 00:20:45.840
[Amit Varma]: a distant state I didn't mean a distant as in it doesn't affect our lives. Of course

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:50.680
[Amit Varma]: it does. It's distant in terms of accountability, seeming accountability but its tentacles are

00:20:50.680 --> 00:20:56.920
[Amit Varma]: all over us. I refer to our state as a predatory state. I'm fascinated by what you said earlier

00:20:56.920 --> 00:21:01.800
[Amit Varma]: because you're right that you know what we make of history sometimes depends on how we've

00:21:01.800 --> 00:21:11.080
[Amit Varma]: studied it and what prism we are looking at it from and what you mentioned about the first

00:21:11.080 --> 00:21:15.680
[Amit Varma]: sort of pushback against colonialism coming from Adivazis and agriculturalists is not

00:21:15.680 --> 00:21:19.280
[Amit Varma]: something I've really read much about. So, why don't you you know give me a little potted

00:21:19.280 --> 00:21:20.280
[Guest]: history.

00:21:20.280 --> 00:21:25.000
[Guest]: I'll send you a booklet which we co-drafted that is one of my mentors who's taught me

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:32.040
[Guest]: so much Ashok Ashok Choudhury who's the part of this union and myself he was kind enough

00:21:32.040 --> 00:21:35.160
[Guest]: to say that I should get a joint byline for it though I think he did a lot of the work

00:21:35.160 --> 00:21:36.160
[Amit Varma]: I did.

00:21:36.160 --> 00:21:39.760
[Guest]: Is it downloadable? So, I'll put it in the show notes and my listeners can download it.

00:21:39.760 --> 00:21:44.600
[Guest]: So, we've done a chapter for this book that is a part of a foreign university publication

00:21:44.600 --> 00:21:49.440
[Guest]: and we also brought out a booklet for the union and CJP and I think it's very important

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:55.000
[Guest]: to look at this because it tells us four or five things it tells us first of all that

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:59.520
[Guest]: coming back to your question that this history is very important history of struggle because

00:21:59.520 --> 00:22:03.680
[Guest]: the history of struggle is the history of actually obtaining your rights and that's

00:22:03.680 --> 00:22:09.400
[Guest]: always a fundamental for any civil liberties activists which I primarily am that no rights

00:22:09.400 --> 00:22:13.400
[Guest]: have come for easy no rights have come for free okay they don't come unless you there's

00:22:13.400 --> 00:22:20.480
[Guest]: a struggle for them worldwide we've seen that from Africa to the United States to any part

00:22:20.480 --> 00:22:25.720
[Guest]: of the world I mean even now I mean if you look at the United States there's still barely

00:22:25.720 --> 00:22:31.120
[Guest]: a recognition of what they've done to their own American Indian people and that conversation

00:22:31.120 --> 00:22:36.040
[Guest]: is beginning to happen in Australia to some extent with the with the indigenous and the

00:22:36.040 --> 00:22:42.640
[Guest]: Maori populations and all and it's a painful conversation because it's not easy but I think

00:22:42.640 --> 00:22:48.200
[Guest]: all of us particularly from the privileged sections need to have that because we we don't

00:22:48.200 --> 00:22:53.120
[Guest]: realize to what extent that appropriation of resources has happened by those of us who

00:22:53.120 --> 00:23:01.840
[Guest]: have come from from privileged sections so coming back to this you know during the COVID

00:23:01.840 --> 00:23:04.880
[Guest]: period in fact which was otherwise a very difficult period because none of us could

00:23:04.880 --> 00:23:10.320
[Guest]: travel as much we normally do and particularly going to some areas we undertook this exercise

00:23:10.320 --> 00:23:16.120
[Guest]: of ensuring that all of us in the I'm not that citizen for justice and peace the organization

00:23:16.120 --> 00:23:20.520
[Guest]: which I represent and also the other one of which I'm vice president which is the Akhil

00:23:20.520 --> 00:23:25.480
[Guest]: Bharatiya Vanjan Shamjivi Union that the in all the units of the unions we should stay

00:23:25.480 --> 00:23:31.720
[Guest]: connected and CJP helped helped helped hugely in this because we said that you know technology

00:23:31.720 --> 00:23:35.920
[Guest]: is such a faraway thing and technology in the village and the Gram Sabha how do you

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:42.000
[Guest]: do it so we sort of did these zoom trainings and the zoom workshops I mean connectivity

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:46.800
[Guest]: India is very we think we are greatly committed very very poor if you look at the non-urban

00:23:46.800 --> 00:23:51.720
[Guest]: areas so all of those were huge challenges we tried to overcome them and we started having

00:23:51.720 --> 00:23:57.480
[Guest]: weekly meetings if what eventually became Gram Sabha meetings on zoom I mean I cannot

00:23:57.480 --> 00:24:01.680
[Guest]: even tell you what that experience was because I could be sitting in Bombay or Pune or Delhi

00:24:01.680 --> 00:24:08.160
[Guest]: wherever I was in that one camera that was in Sonbhadra in UP where Sukala was the president

00:24:08.160 --> 00:24:13.760
[Guest]: of our union she's the most amazing woman she's been jailed twice in her lifetime and

00:24:13.760 --> 00:24:17.760
[Guest]: unlike me when she was in jail for a month she didn't eat food she just survived on fruit

00:24:17.760 --> 00:24:23.680
[Guest]: and milk I don't know how she did that so she would be sitting on her camera on a phone

00:24:23.680 --> 00:24:30.920
[Guest]: phone camera with at least 150 women in the same room and each one would have their turn

00:24:30.920 --> 00:24:35.160
[Guest]: to speak on the zoom and all of us would be able to listen so it was amazingly humbling

00:24:35.160 --> 00:24:42.520
[Guest]: and democratizing process and through that we decided collectively that knowledge about

00:24:42.520 --> 00:24:50.080
[Guest]: the constitution and Adivasi rights and the making of the Forest Rights Act of 2006 which

00:24:50.080 --> 00:24:55.240
[Guest]: is our mantra for the Adivasi and indigenous movement because it's the law that came about

00:24:55.240 --> 00:24:59.400
[Guest]: because of these collective struggles in the land and forest because it turns the whole

00:24:59.400 --> 00:25:04.840
[Guest]: notion of elite conservation on its head that you can't really conserve environment without

00:25:04.840 --> 00:25:09.440
[Guest]: protecting the rights of the people who've lived in those environs you know and because

00:25:09.440 --> 00:25:15.600
[Guest]: they are the best conservers of that it's not a hostile positioning it has to be a collaborative

00:25:15.600 --> 00:25:21.760
[Guest]: thing so when this started to happen you realize that they were also during the COVID period

00:25:21.760 --> 00:25:26.920
[Guest]: commemorating their histories all the time so they were saying we will start our own

00:25:26.920 --> 00:25:32.440
[Guest]: kind of schools which will be shifting schools which will be telling our own histories and

00:25:32.440 --> 00:25:37.000
[Guest]: the histories of these struggles are alive to them we think that you know we have to

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:42.960
[Guest]: dig them up from the odd historian who actually has had the grace to look at Adivasi struggles

00:25:42.960 --> 00:25:48.880
[Guest]: in English or Bengali and the Bengali translation or Hindi translation and there have been some

00:25:48.880 --> 00:25:55.480
[Guest]: amazing bureaucrats also from the IS and earlier from the British colonial period who documented

00:25:55.480 --> 00:26:01.080
[Guest]: some of these despite being part of a colonial hierarchy and you collect this information

00:26:01.080 --> 00:26:06.960
[Guest]: and then you know these struggles are being actually today celebrated commemorated as

00:26:06.960 --> 00:26:12.000
[Guest]: well they haven't forgotten them but then you give it a discussion gives it a deeper

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:17.160
[Guest]: form and a context you connect it up with today's struggles and through those exercises

00:26:17.160 --> 00:26:21.560
[Guest]: that one and a half two year period and through that we saw the farmers struggle okay and

00:26:21.560 --> 00:26:26.760
[Guest]: I want to mention this because it was an amazing thing what what happened to India during that

00:26:26.760 --> 00:26:31.600
[Guest]: pandemic particularly the second half I mean you saw that from June of 2020 and then you

00:26:31.600 --> 00:26:38.480
[Guest]: saw November 2020 and you saw how that I mean where was the pandemic for those for the farmers

00:26:38.480 --> 00:26:45.080
[Guest]: who went and sat at outside Delhi you know and I mean they compelled and impelled all

00:26:45.080 --> 00:26:49.520
[Guest]: of us to to look at their struggle and they brought history and context to their struggle

00:26:49.520 --> 00:26:54.520
[Guest]: because everything they were saying particularly the BKU Ugran and all they were talking about

00:26:54.520 --> 00:27:01.760
[Guest]: Bhagat Singh's grandfather and Punjab and you know what what the what the impoverishment

00:27:01.760 --> 00:27:06.360
[Guest]: of colonial rule meant and how our policies are taking us back in that direction by not

00:27:06.360 --> 00:27:12.000
[Guest]: by passing laws that are going to corporatize agriculture completely and leave the bargaining

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:19.280
[Guest]: power of the farmer out of the question so you know all these things are very very crucial

00:27:19.280 --> 00:27:26.080
[Guest]: so I think for me it has been a learning through actually working with people's struggles and

00:27:26.080 --> 00:27:30.960
[Guest]: having the humility to always understand that you don't know it all in fact you're in a

00:27:30.960 --> 00:27:36.840
[Guest]: constant process or yes you bring something of your experience and learning to the process

00:27:36.840 --> 00:27:40.920
[Guest]: and that's why it's collaborative and important but there's so much you need to learn actually

00:27:40.920 --> 00:27:45.200
[Guest]: from people's struggle and you know like we were talking earlier that we are a strongly

00:27:45.200 --> 00:27:50.520
[Guest]: oral history tradition you know and if you remember the Pathalkadi movement you know

00:27:50.520 --> 00:27:56.560
[Guest]: which father Stan and others when father Stan died in judicial tragically died in I mean

00:27:56.560 --> 00:28:03.200
[Guest]: to the judicial murder but that Pathalkadi's struggle was doing just this in in Tharkhand

00:28:03.200 --> 00:28:09.840
[Guest]: you know what were they saying they were saying that we will on stones and on pillars put

00:28:09.840 --> 00:28:15.400
[Guest]: up our constitutional rights which have been granted to us so whether it is schedule nine

00:28:15.400 --> 00:28:20.600
[Guest]: or schedule five or the constitution or whether it is article the directive principles which

00:28:20.600 --> 00:28:26.400
[Guest]: give Adivasi rights or whether it is a Niyam Giri judgment or any of the judgments that

00:28:26.400 --> 00:28:30.680
[Guest]: the court has given us we will put that down so tomorrow when the forest official comes

00:28:30.680 --> 00:28:34.000
[Guest]: and pretends not to know of these laws which have been passed by the Indian Parliament

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:40.760
[Guest]: we'll say we'll tell you we'll do a legal education for you you know and there is this

00:28:40.760 --> 00:28:46.480
[Guest]: very strong belief that the constitution is ours among people of this country that the

00:28:46.480 --> 00:28:54.600
[Guest]: laws the progressive laws passed the recognition of land rights recognition of forest rights

00:28:54.600 --> 00:29:00.480
[Guest]: the land acquisition law which was amended and by the UPA to government before the present

00:29:00.480 --> 00:29:06.560
[Guest]: regime overturned it again all of these were not because the UPA to government wanted to

00:29:06.560 --> 00:29:12.320
[Guest]: give it it was because there was being a coalition government being not a authoritarian strong

00:29:12.320 --> 00:29:16.640
[Guest]: government they were compelled to listen to voices from the ground and that's what a democracy

00:29:16.640 --> 00:29:22.600
[Guest]: is so I think coming back to your question of history and Adivasi history it all boils

00:29:22.600 --> 00:29:29.520
[Guest]: down to working with communities on an equitable basis equal basis and realizing that any struggle

00:29:29.520 --> 00:29:34.680
[Guest]: that you're involved in today has to hark back to your past because eventually you are

00:29:34.680 --> 00:29:41.280
[Guest]: based on your symbolisms your I mean the strong women's presence in Adivasi struggles has

00:29:41.280 --> 00:29:47.960
[Guest]: been there from the beginning the very strong women's presence number of women lost to the

00:29:47.960 --> 00:29:52.960
[Guest]: battle against communal colonialism has been huge they know the names they know the name

00:29:52.960 --> 00:29:59.160
[Guest]: they sing songs to them they know that they advocated education for the kids they educated

00:29:59.160 --> 00:30:03.800
[Guest]: the rights over forest produce and that it should not that should not go to the colonial

00:30:03.800 --> 00:30:10.960
[Guest]: powers and the forest bureaucracy but unfortunately there's always been this distance between

00:30:10.960 --> 00:30:17.520
[Guest]: urban and rural and Adivasi and non-Adivasi and hence it's taken a while for the rest

00:30:17.520 --> 00:30:20.680
[Guest]: of us to open our eyes to it.

00:30:20.680 --> 00:30:24.680
[Amit Varma]: So there are about five different directions I want to digress in but I'll just pick one

00:30:24.680 --> 00:30:30.720
[Amit Varma]: and digress in that and it's a slightly long-winded question which I've explored in past episodes

00:30:30.720 --> 00:30:38.160
[Amit Varma]: with different people there are two kinds of forces that we have seen in modern times

00:30:38.160 --> 00:30:45.680
[Amit Varma]: and the first force which comes with urbanization and capitalism and all of those with all their

00:30:45.680 --> 00:30:51.680
[Amit Varma]: you know other positive effects is of a certain kind of homogenization which leads to a loss

00:30:51.680 --> 00:30:55.480
[Amit Varma]: in diversity I mean one metaphor for this is a Cavendish banana which is of course a

00:30:55.480 --> 00:31:01.640
[Amit Varma]: banana that we exported to the world and then you know it made sense in the US economies

00:31:01.640 --> 00:31:06.920
[Amit Varma]: of scale whatever then it was brought back to India and now it is kind of killing all

00:31:06.920 --> 00:31:11.440
[Amit Varma]: indigenous sorts of bananas and that's an example with bananas where your diversity

00:31:11.440 --> 00:31:17.160
[Amit Varma]: is driven out and everything is becoming homogeneous and rice is the same and I had assumed that

00:31:17.160 --> 00:31:22.360
[Amit Varma]: there's a similar thing happening with languages and dialects like one of my previous guests

00:31:22.360 --> 00:31:26.520
[Amit Varma]: Vinay Singhal not the Hindutva Vinay Singhal this is a young entrepreneur who runs a company

00:31:26.520 --> 00:31:32.320
[Amit Varma]: called Stage what he once told me ki you know bhasha sheher mein hoti hai boli sheher ke

00:31:32.320 --> 00:31:37.280
[Amit Varma]: bahar hoti hai you know the languages of the city the dialects are outside and I had assumed

00:31:37.280 --> 00:31:42.320
[Amit Varma]: and lamented that the logical direction is going to be that dialects are gradually going

00:31:42.320 --> 00:31:47.360
[Amit Varma]: to die out because when a young person who is from a village goes to a city the incentives

00:31:47.360 --> 00:31:51.600
[Amit Varma]: will be to fit in and to speak in their dominant language so you might forget your dialect

00:31:51.600 --> 00:31:57.920
[Amit Varma]: of Hindi and speak Hindi and gradually that's what happens what Vinay is doing with a stage

00:31:57.920 --> 00:32:04.960
[Amit Varma]: is demonstrating the opposite effect where a stage is an OTT for Bharat but it's not

00:32:04.960 --> 00:32:10.240
[Amit Varma]: an OTT for Indian languages like Hindi and Punjabi it's an OTT for dialects like Haryanvi

00:32:10.240 --> 00:32:15.920
[Amit Varma]: and Rajasthani and is doing incredibly well and again capitalism playing a part technology

00:32:15.920 --> 00:32:21.120
[Amit Varma]: playing a part that individuals are being empowered with the means of production and

00:32:21.120 --> 00:32:26.520
[Amit Varma]: in some cases perhaps a means of communication where they can keep their culture alive where

00:32:26.520 --> 00:32:32.320
[Amit Varma]: things don't have to scale it's almost an opposite of these forces of homogenization

00:32:32.320 --> 00:32:37.200
[Amit Varma]: and I want to ask you about this because when you speak of all these different oral history

00:32:37.200 --> 00:32:42.000
[Amit Varma]: traditions stories that have come down the danger always is that these stories will be

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:48.360
[Amit Varma]: lost because you move to a city or you know gradually over time things erode and things

00:32:48.360 --> 00:32:53.360
[Amit Varma]: wither away and God knows how much we've lost but then there is also the hope that people

00:32:53.360 --> 00:33:00.820
[Amit Varma]: will instead of being embarrassed by their origins can take pride in it can find community

00:33:00.820 --> 00:33:06.160
[Amit Varma]: in it and and can you know take it into a different direction so it's not a very well

00:33:06.160 --> 00:33:11.200
[Amit Varma]: articulated question slightly long-winded but just looking at these two forces since

00:33:11.200 --> 00:33:17.360
[Amit Varma]: you work so much at the grassroots and on the ground with such a wide variety of people

00:33:17.360 --> 00:33:22.740
[Amit Varma]: what is your sense of this that is it something that we should be hopeful that people who

00:33:22.740 --> 00:33:27.760
[Amit Varma]: earlier did not have a voice or a way to preserve their memories and their traditions do they

00:33:27.760 --> 00:33:35.120
[Guest]: now have more of it I come back to this whole business of history and I've learned so much

00:33:35.120 --> 00:33:40.360
[Guest]: from many of our most renowned historians whether it is Romila, Thapar, Rocky and Panikkar

00:33:40.360 --> 00:33:45.160
[Guest]: and I'm talking about the 80s 80s and 90s when we used to hold workshops with them first

00:33:45.160 --> 00:33:50.280
[Guest]: to learn and then I organized workshops with them for teachers and you've got a great interview

00:33:50.280 --> 00:33:54.680
[Guest]: of Romila ji also I'll link that from the show notes for me the most I mean and for

00:33:54.680 --> 00:34:01.240
[Guest]: them I organized three workshops where they came and actually interacted with the school

00:34:01.240 --> 00:34:08.040
[Guest]: teachers from about maybe 40 schools in Bombay two schools each and three four days they

00:34:08.040 --> 00:34:14.560
[Guest]: interacted and so and my thought behind that because Khoj the pedagogy of Khoj was evolving

00:34:14.560 --> 00:34:20.480
[Guest]: at that stage now we've got about 54 modules going and resources permitting we can do that

00:34:20.480 --> 00:34:24.400
[Guest]: or we can't do that kind of workshop all the time but we are editing it and we're trying

00:34:24.400 --> 00:34:32.200
[Guest]: to make it available so we can use that input idea being that the those original thinkers

00:34:32.200 --> 00:34:36.320
[Guest]: and historians who are actually looking at history in a particular way should interact

00:34:36.320 --> 00:34:42.600
[Guest]: directly with the carriers of that history into the classroom so that that pedagogy of

00:34:42.600 --> 00:34:49.820
[Guest]: a non-didactic teaching not no final full stop always a question mark have the humility

00:34:49.820 --> 00:34:53.560
[Guest]: and courage to say you don't know something and you look it up and come back and the child

00:34:53.560 --> 00:34:59.240
[Guest]: will respect you more the young mind will respect you more not less all of that went

00:34:59.240 --> 00:35:03.080
[Guest]: into this exercise so I remember those kind of early days when I was also sort of learning

00:35:03.080 --> 00:35:09.720
[Guest]: all this and I'm still learning is that they would say that you know and that's when Narcissus

00:35:09.720 --> 00:35:16.280
[Guest]: of course it's going to be 100 years old in 1925 into 2025 so it's worked very hard for

00:35:16.280 --> 00:35:20.920
[Guest]: what it's done apart from acting having obnoxious amounts of money which it shouldn't have but

00:35:20.920 --> 00:35:29.120
[Guest]: that's not the point that one of the bulwarks against authoritarian supremacism is local

00:35:29.120 --> 00:35:34.240
[Guest]: histories and diversity and pluralism okay this was always what we said and came up with

00:35:34.240 --> 00:35:39.080
[Guest]: at the end of these discussions and workshops that and we need to do this at various levels

00:35:39.080 --> 00:35:44.680
[Guest]: we need to do it as at the at the finer academic historical level where there's a certain rigor

00:35:44.680 --> 00:35:50.960
[Guest]: of the discipline where local histories emerge and maybe even contradict the national narrative

00:35:50.960 --> 00:35:56.640
[Guest]: doesn't matter let the let the dialectic emerge but we also need to do the level of people

00:35:56.640 --> 00:36:00.960
[Guest]: and communities which is the question you are asking so I think it's very important

00:36:00.960 --> 00:36:05.120
[Guest]: and this continues to be a passion for some of us you know and we are also doing so many

00:36:05.120 --> 00:36:09.480
[Guest]: things that it doesn't always happen the way we want it to happen but but wherever I go

00:36:09.480 --> 00:36:13.480
[Guest]: wherever I speak into workshops speak about civil rights liberties I keep trying to say

00:36:13.480 --> 00:36:17.680
[Guest]: that put together a group of citizens whether it's Belgaum whether it is Mangalore whether

00:36:17.680 --> 00:36:24.720
[Guest]: it is Chiplun a tiny seaside town in Maharashtra put together you'll always have those 10-15

00:36:24.720 --> 00:36:29.720
[Guest]: people 5 people 4 people who are obsessed with your past and your history and your tradition

00:36:29.720 --> 00:36:35.640
[Guest]: put them together meet regularly start documenting and put it out you know because I think that

00:36:35.640 --> 00:36:42.640
[Guest]: is our only bulwark against this this top-down homogenization which has a sinister political

00:36:42.640 --> 00:36:47.400
[Guest]: motive without question I think this is what we've tried to bring into the coach classroom

00:36:47.400 --> 00:36:51.720
[Guest]: and if you give me a few minutes I want to share this because it was fascinating for

00:36:51.720 --> 00:36:58.720
[Guest]: us when we evolved these modules and one of the modules is which we do I mean unfortunately

00:36:58.720 --> 00:37:03.200
[Guest]: because they're dealing with India school structure and the classroom and we don't make

00:37:03.200 --> 00:37:08.600
[Guest]: it a honeymoon experiment with those special schools we've we've decided to look at the

00:37:08.600 --> 00:37:14.120
[Guest]: school as it is for everybody you know which is a problem but we have to tackle it so we've

00:37:14.120 --> 00:37:19.080
[Guest]: tried to do it in middle school like 5th 6th 7th a three-year program not not necessarily

00:37:19.080 --> 00:37:23.840
[Guest]: go 8th and 9th only special classes because the whole exam pressure gets too much etc

00:37:23.840 --> 00:37:28.920
[Guest]: so towards the end between the 6th and 7th we do this migratory history model you know

00:37:28.920 --> 00:37:34.720
[Guest]: which is my history the child's history the idea is to introduce to the young mind which

00:37:34.720 --> 00:37:41.560
[Guest]: is about 10 11 12 by then 11 12 by then that let's explore your family history each each

00:37:41.560 --> 00:37:46.000
[Guest]: each one of you need to explore your history and how do you we don't finish it in one class

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:51.600
[Guest]: ever it goes through three or four sessions once a week maybe you come back to it even

00:37:51.600 --> 00:37:57.880
[Guest]: a month later two months later idea is ask questions in your family and in your community

00:37:57.880 --> 00:38:03.440
[Guest]: where are we from which village which district which state which language do we speak do

00:38:03.440 --> 00:38:09.280
[Guest]: we have connections with that with that place still do we go back if not where did we directly

00:38:09.280 --> 00:38:13.080
[Guest]: come from there to Mumbai or Pune wherever the class is being held or did we go somewhere

00:38:13.080 --> 00:38:19.960
[Guest]: in between and start chasing this start chasing it make notes jot it down if you ask enough

00:38:19.960 --> 00:38:23.840
[Guest]: questions you'll find a couple of people who are willing to kind of wax eloquent about

00:38:23.840 --> 00:38:28.680
[Guest]: this once you get them to wax eloquent cross check the sources a little bit cross check

00:38:28.680 --> 00:38:34.480
[Guest]: with two three people the facts and all that and start penning this history migratory history

00:38:34.480 --> 00:38:41.360
[Guest]: of say Dhruv Prajapati or whatever the name is and start writing it down and then at the

00:38:41.360 --> 00:38:47.000
[Guest]: end of nine months one and a half years whenever it's ready when these are sort of shared in

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:52.760
[Guest]: a live classroom atmosphere I cannot begin to even describe to you what happens in the

00:38:52.760 --> 00:39:02.320
[Guest]: classroom because the entire temperature changes the classroom sort of almost becomes from

00:39:02.320 --> 00:39:09.560
[Guest]: a kind of a uniform straight in a line benches it suddenly becomes multicolored colorful

00:39:09.560 --> 00:39:15.200
[Guest]: somebody brings in a Kannada word somebody brings in a Telugu word Tulu word Urdu couplet

00:39:15.200 --> 00:39:21.560
[Guest]: a funny story a tragic story and the diversity is really lived and felt because that's how

00:39:21.560 --> 00:39:26.880
[Guest]: all our realities are whether Mumbai might be more than that some cities might be less

00:39:26.880 --> 00:39:33.960
[Guest]: but I show me one one one classroom any part of India or the world where this diversity

00:39:33.960 --> 00:39:39.640
[Guest]: does not exist we are all we are all migrated from somewhere to somewhere we are all creatures

00:39:39.640 --> 00:39:44.320
[Guest]: of movement and travel that's what human beings are and maybe some are not but even that is

00:39:44.320 --> 00:39:51.160
[Guest]: very interesting so I think that whole concept that you understand each other through the

00:39:51.160 --> 00:39:56.160
[Guest]: story through the language through the past through the present is very important for

00:39:56.160 --> 00:40:00.640
[Guest]: the young mind to develop and if you do that I feel and that's been one of our reasons

00:40:00.640 --> 00:40:06.120
[Guest]: why we are doing COGE even now after 20 32 years is that it's a very small thing it it

00:40:06.120 --> 00:40:11.560
[Guest]: it'll take a long time but but but the young minds who go through it never give up that

00:40:11.560 --> 00:40:18.640
[Guest]: questioning and I don't believe in this business of teaching secularism or teaching the Constitution

00:40:18.640 --> 00:40:25.000
[Guest]: you can't do what you can do is if you want to share an understanding of article 14 and

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:30.080
[Guest]: 15 which is equality and non-discrimination then you have to teach them about discrimination

00:40:30.080 --> 00:40:35.200
[Guest]: share stories about discrimination and struggles against discrimination so that's the only

00:40:35.200 --> 00:40:41.960
[Guest]: be a sense of what that article is will actually take root in that young mind and then you

00:40:41.960 --> 00:40:46.160
[Guest]: at the end of 13 years might get a citizen that is a questioning citizen and not just

00:40:46.160 --> 00:40:51.800
[Guest]: somebody who's looking for job and pay hikes so I think that has been the that has been

00:40:51.800 --> 00:40:58.240
[Guest]: the basis of this whole thing when we look at homogenization when we look at authoritarianism

00:40:58.240 --> 00:41:05.120
[Guest]: it's all connected why is there this obsession whether you look at the fundamentalism of

00:41:05.120 --> 00:41:11.800
[Guest]: political Islam or whether you look at Hindutva or if you look at extremely rigid Buddhism

00:41:11.800 --> 00:41:17.080
[Guest]: that Sri Lanka also threw up when it massacred so many Tamils and not Sri Lanka why is this

00:41:17.080 --> 00:41:23.160
[Guest]: obsession with homogenizing and uniformity it's as if it's as if diversity itself is

00:41:23.160 --> 00:41:28.600
[Guest]: a threat and therefore the patriarchy comes in the rigidity comes in the attacks on women

00:41:28.600 --> 00:41:33.600
[Guest]: come in all of this so I think the ability to connect some of all of these things is

00:41:33.600 --> 00:41:39.080
[Guest]: very very important and can we do that can we do that in our struggles can we form alliances

00:41:39.080 --> 00:41:45.440
[Guest]: in our struggles this has been an abiding concern and question and I don't think we've

00:41:45.440 --> 00:41:51.400
[Guest]: always succeeded but I think the effort itself is very important effort itself is very important

00:41:51.400 --> 00:41:56.600
[Guest]: because you're able to see that not just this struggle which you've taken up just now is

00:41:56.600 --> 00:42:00.760
[Guest]: important of course it is but there are also many other myriad struggles that need to be

00:42:00.760 --> 00:42:07.440
[Guest]: looked at to be able to question this absolutely crude homogenization that we are seeing.

00:42:07.440 --> 00:42:12.520
[Amit Varma]: I find this story you've told of the magic you created in the classroom very resonant

00:42:12.520 --> 00:42:17.880
[Amit Varma]: because it feeds in with a theme that I think about a fair bit which is the importance of

00:42:17.880 --> 00:42:22.480
[Amit Varma]: the concrete in our lives like what often happens is that if we just think in terms

00:42:22.480 --> 00:42:29.360
[Amit Varma]: of abstractions like nationalism or purity or race or the other or Hindu or Muslim those

00:42:29.360 --> 00:42:36.040
[Amit Varma]: abstractions can be dangerous and can lead us down you know problematic paths but the

00:42:36.040 --> 00:42:39.960
[Amit Varma]: moment you make it concrete and I see that's what's happening in this classroom that's

00:42:39.960 --> 00:42:44.680
[Amit Varma]: what it seems like to me that it's almost like a show don't tell brought to life that

00:42:44.680 --> 00:42:51.680
[Amit Varma]: each child is making herself concrete by talking about her past and where she's come from and

00:42:51.680 --> 00:42:56.520
[Amit Varma]: you know showing her authentic self also in a sense and showing the joy and that and everyone

00:42:56.520 --> 00:43:01.200
[Amit Varma]: can then relate to each other in a different way it's a lesson about discrimination in

00:43:01.200 --> 00:43:05.560
[Amit Varma]: the most beautiful way because it's a lesson about the joy of diversity which is automatically

00:43:05.560 --> 00:43:12.760
[Amit Varma]: an anti-discriminatory lesson right so that that's a lovely story here's my next a digressive

00:43:12.760 --> 00:43:18.120
[Amit Varma]: question and obviously that cliche is of course true whatever you say about India the opposite

00:43:18.120 --> 00:43:23.680
[Amit Varma]: is also true right so we are deeply illiberal in so many ways gender caste whatever but

00:43:23.680 --> 00:43:30.880
[Amit Varma]: there is a lived liberalism which you can you know see in our languages in our cuisine

00:43:30.880 --> 00:43:35.960
[Amit Varma]: and our clothes assimilations from everywhere and you've also spoke at the start of this

00:43:35.960 --> 00:43:40.200
[Amit Varma]: conversation about how Maharashtra has had much older traditions in the RSS which go

00:43:40.200 --> 00:43:46.760
[Amit Varma]: back which are syncretic tolerant which celebrate you know differences but here's the thing

00:43:46.760 --> 00:43:52.120
[Amit Varma]: my sense and we were chatting about this at lunch and it's a theme I keep going back to

00:43:52.120 --> 00:43:57.520
[Amit Varma]: is that if there is one way in which I have realized I was wrong about the world it is

00:43:57.520 --> 00:44:03.040
[Amit Varma]: that you know growing up in my little elite English-speaking bubble I always thought that

00:44:03.040 --> 00:44:07.640
[Amit Varma]: you know India is broadly tolerant we are liberal there are fringes but that's okay

00:44:07.640 --> 00:44:13.280
[Amit Varma]: you know we are what we are and my sense and I can perhaps get too pessimistic about this

00:44:13.280 --> 00:44:21.920
[Amit Varma]: is that no that you know we are the bubble and society is always been extremely illiberal

00:44:21.920 --> 00:44:26.760
[Amit Varma]: and these strands that we see in political Hindutva today they're not recent they've

00:44:26.760 --> 00:44:32.960
[Amit Varma]: been like I did an episode with Akshay Mukul on the Gita Press and all fantastic book and

00:44:32.960 --> 00:44:40.600
[Amit Varma]: all of these issues from you know love jihad and cow protection and conversions all of

00:44:40.600 --> 00:44:45.880
[Amit Varma]: these were live issues exactly a hundred years ago as well right and if you see sort of the

00:44:45.880 --> 00:44:50.480
[Amit Varma]: sales of the books on the Gita Press including their manuals telling women how to behave

00:44:50.480 --> 00:44:57.220
[Amit Varma]: and innocent in sanskari ways and so on and so forth you realize that this is a very big

00:44:57.220 --> 00:45:04.480
[Amit Varma]: in our society and therefore one begins to wonder about whether the experiment that we

00:45:04.480 --> 00:45:10.440
[Amit Varma]: tried with the kind of constitution that we had was it bound to fail because what we seem

00:45:10.440 --> 00:45:15.480
[Amit Varma]: to have done is we took a liberal constitution not as liberal as I would like but still much

00:45:15.480 --> 00:45:20.960
[Amit Varma]: more liberal than society and imposed it on an illiberal society and assumed that the

00:45:20.960 --> 00:45:26.120
[Amit Varma]: job was over that we are doing it top-down things will take care of themselves you know

00:45:26.120 --> 00:45:30.720
[Amit Varma]: Madhav Khosla in a brilliant book an episode with me describes a constitution as a pedagogic

00:45:30.720 --> 00:45:39.360
[Amit Varma]: exercise and it seems that politics has caught up with society and therefore where again

00:45:39.360 --> 00:45:44.440
[Amit Varma]: I'd look pessimistically at what you said about at some point something's going to give

00:45:44.440 --> 00:45:48.960
[Amit Varma]: at some you know I don't know if at some point something's going to give because the majority

00:45:48.960 --> 00:45:53.840
[Amit Varma]: is having its way now who's going to do the rebelling it's not that society is being forced

00:45:53.840 --> 00:45:58.520
[Amit Varma]: into a direction against its will or whatever you know this horrible direction that we are

00:45:58.520 --> 00:46:03.920
[Amit Varma]: going in seems to be if the majority aren't actively clamoring for it they are perfectly

00:46:03.920 --> 00:46:09.280
[Amit Varma]: content with it which is you know obviously it's a very pessimistic view and I know you're

00:46:09.280 --> 00:46:16.320
[Amit Varma]: not so pessimistic so I mean what's what's your sense of this am I being too negative

00:46:16.320 --> 00:46:22.320
[Guest]: no I just it's it's a it's a kind of expected question and it's a question that is that

00:46:22.320 --> 00:46:27.120
[Guest]: needs to be asked if you like but I just would like to take a little bit of issue with say

00:46:27.120 --> 00:46:32.480
[Guest]: the proposition that Madhav would make or whatever because I think it shows very little

00:46:32.480 --> 00:46:39.160
[Guest]: regard for what went into the making of the constitution I mean to think that the constitution

00:46:39.160 --> 00:46:44.040
[Guest]: or the constituent assembly debates that resulted in the constitution and to forget that the

00:46:44.040 --> 00:46:49.560
[Guest]: constituent assembly debates had the partition bang in the middle of it and the fact that

00:46:49.560 --> 00:46:55.040
[Guest]: the constitution actually emerged after the 150 175 years of the struggle against the

00:46:55.040 --> 00:47:01.680
[Guest]: British I think it really disregards the entire sacrifices or the pains of the national movement

00:47:01.680 --> 00:47:06.920
[Guest]: against British colonialism so I just like to contest that very strongly because I think

00:47:06.920 --> 00:47:12.080
[Guest]: to say that it was a pedagogic constitution is actually to disregard that the what I said

00:47:12.080 --> 00:47:16.800
[Guest]: right in the beginning that the values that were thrown up from the freedom struggle from

00:47:16.800 --> 00:47:22.160
[Guest]: the national movement also harked back to much earlier struggles but they coalesced

00:47:22.160 --> 00:47:26.800
[Guest]: in a certain way and they represented a large and vast section of our people in fact I think

00:47:26.800 --> 00:47:31.520
[Guest]: the problem is with liberals who think that we are the cocooned minority but I think the

00:47:31.520 --> 00:47:37.560
[Guest]: vast vast vast section of these people of the people of this country have actually battled

00:47:37.560 --> 00:47:42.840
[Guest]: inequality and oppression of various kinds under British rule and they actually were

00:47:42.840 --> 00:47:48.360
[Guest]: part of the movement against the British so I want to repeat that and I think therefore

00:47:48.360 --> 00:47:53.800
[Guest]: the values that were then sort of nichodoed and put into the constitution came as much

00:47:53.800 --> 00:48:00.280
[Guest]: from there as much as from the higher intellect as we like to think of it of people I mean

00:48:00.280 --> 00:48:05.720
[Guest]: why was Babasaheb Ambedkar chosen I mean that question I think Madhav Goswami should also

00:48:05.720 --> 00:48:12.040
[Guest]: answer because why was Dr. Babasaheb Ambedkar a man a young man who when he was a young

00:48:12.040 --> 00:48:22.400
[Guest]: boy of maybe 12 or 13 in the Elphinstone school Mumbai sitting in a classroom and a brilliant

00:48:22.400 --> 00:48:31.640
[Guest]: mind and a maths problem is put to him and nobody in the class is able to answer and

00:48:31.640 --> 00:48:36.200
[Guest]: he puts his hand up confidently and then the teacher is compelled to allow him to come

00:48:36.200 --> 00:48:42.200
[Guest]: up to the blackboard to write down the five steps solution to the maths problem which

00:48:42.200 --> 00:48:47.600
[Guest]: he does he solves it correctly and the attention of the class by the time he's reached the

00:48:47.600 --> 00:48:52.760
[Guest]: last the answer is not on the fact that he's got it correct but the fact that a quote-unquote

00:48:52.760 --> 00:48:58.000
[Guest]: untouchable has reached the blackboard because all their tiffin boxes are behind and therefore

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:03.800
[Guest]: they will not eat their food anymore because now it has been polluted now this is the man

00:49:03.800 --> 00:49:11.200
[Guest]: chosen quote-unquote not chosen he's the man who obviously the person to write the constitution

00:49:11.200 --> 00:49:16.880
[Guest]: and how can we therefore ever say that the majority of this country are sworn to a kind

00:49:16.880 --> 00:49:22.160
[Guest]: of a majoritarian authoritarian deal no I think there is a certainly the subaltern there's

00:49:22.160 --> 00:49:29.760
[Guest]: a whole section of the underbelly and that has grown from the meagre 0.5 or 10 percent

00:49:29.760 --> 00:49:35.360
[Guest]: of the Jan Sangh once had to maybe even a 30 percent or 35 percent or 40 percent of

00:49:35.360 --> 00:49:42.120
[Guest]: the population but I do not think that I will accept that it is a hundred percent what has

00:49:42.120 --> 00:49:48.080
[Guest]: happened for sure is that the rest whether it is 20% or 60% we can argue numbers but

00:49:48.080 --> 00:49:52.200
[Guest]: I think they have been silenced at various levels particularly the ones who are in a

00:49:52.200 --> 00:49:58.040
[Guest]: position to speak one is a kind of a sense of self-preservation and fear that we would

00:49:58.040 --> 00:50:03.960
[Guest]: not like to be the next persons who are a target whether it be through state agencies

00:50:03.960 --> 00:50:09.440
[Guest]: or through any sort of vilification and there's a larger section our problem is the Indian

00:50:09.440 --> 00:50:14.520
[Guest]: middle class which is just too obnoxiously large by world standards which actually does

00:50:14.520 --> 00:50:19.320
[Guest]: not care one way or the other it does not care either whether we are going to be a democratic

00:50:19.320 --> 00:50:24.160
[Guest]: constitutional state or an authoritarian state because it's navigating its life but they

00:50:24.160 --> 00:50:28.680
[Guest]: are not the majority of the population they are obnoxiously large but they are not the

00:50:28.680 --> 00:50:34.120
[Guest]: majority of the population so I think it's the fragmentation and the silencing which

00:50:34.120 --> 00:50:40.000
[Guest]: is not letting the rest sort of come together in a way that would give hope to everybody

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:45.040
[Guest]: that something is happening if you are looking and working at the grassroots if you are looking

00:50:45.040 --> 00:50:52.680
[Guest]: at the kind of the struggles in various parts of the country and there are myriads of them

00:50:52.680 --> 00:50:57.120
[Guest]: I think one will realize that it's not an entirely hope it is fairly hopeless but not

00:50:57.120 --> 00:51:02.320
[Guest]: entirely I'm not a stupid optimist but I'd also like to say that the hugest and biggest

00:51:02.320 --> 00:51:08.360
[Guest]: abdication of the last decade and a half has been by the media and I think all of us in

00:51:08.360 --> 00:51:12.160
[Guest]: some way or the other are products and have been associated with the media so I think

00:51:12.160 --> 00:51:17.640
[Guest]: we need to understand what this means you know and I remember when I did these long

00:51:17.640 --> 00:51:23.640
[Guest]: interviews with Sainath who's really interrogated this thing very very deeply and of course

00:51:23.640 --> 00:51:29.240
[Guest]: there are many others that when you know he said it's not it's a kind of a triangle hold

00:51:29.240 --> 00:51:38.040
[Guest]: on Indian democracy now through the corporatization of the media and the politicization party

00:51:38.040 --> 00:51:44.500
[Guest]: politicization I mean media has to be political but you have if one party dominates the ownership

00:51:44.500 --> 00:51:52.200
[Guest]: of the media and corporates and those same people are then now the dominant in Parliament

00:51:52.200 --> 00:51:57.600
[Guest]: so then when he calculates like Sainath does that how many percentage of our parliamentarians

00:51:57.600 --> 00:52:03.840
[Guest]: are billionaires and which industries do they represent then it's mining telecom and television

00:52:03.840 --> 00:52:12.680
[Guest]: companies so then you know that the digital communications industry your commercial television

00:52:12.680 --> 00:52:17.880
[Guest]: and your political representation is all the same and therefore you're unlikely to see

00:52:17.880 --> 00:52:23.480
[Guest]: a debate happening there on what you were talking about which is a homogenized banana

00:52:23.480 --> 00:52:30.680
[Guest]: or the rice varieties which are being completely finished off because of the kind of priorities

00:52:30.680 --> 00:52:36.640
[Guest]: we are giving to agriculture forget a lynching or a Mohammed Clark you won't even have a

00:52:36.640 --> 00:52:44.360
[Guest]: debate on homogenization of agriculture because it's not in the interest of you know the section

00:52:44.360 --> 00:52:48.720
[Guest]: that would benefit from this homogenization who are sitting in Parliament to do that so

00:52:48.720 --> 00:52:53.520
[Guest]: actually therefore we are talking about as in when and if the resistance happens in our

00:52:53.520 --> 00:52:58.480
[Guest]: lifetime and I hope it does even if it doesn't seem very imminent is that you really need

00:52:58.480 --> 00:53:04.320
[Guest]: to be looking at electoral reform judicial reform media ownership changes you know so

00:53:04.320 --> 00:53:10.400
[Guest]: you need to look we need to look at judicial reform court and you need to look at so many

00:53:10.400 --> 00:53:15.200
[Guest]: things being turned on their head which is like individual and collective struggles that

00:53:15.200 --> 00:53:21.000
[Guest]: encompass all of this and is that feasible is that happening can it happen is of course

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:25.160
[Guest]: seems so overwhelming that we most of the time feel it cannot happen I mean just look

00:53:25.160 --> 00:53:29.800
[Guest]: at what the election commission is doing look at the electoral bonds issue I mean it's so

00:53:29.800 --> 00:53:36.400
[Guest]: brazenly non-transparent it is brazenly non-transparent you know and then therefore there's inordinate

00:53:36.400 --> 00:53:40.320
[Guest]: hope that is required from the judiciary and will the supreme court cope therefore these

00:53:40.320 --> 00:53:44.120
[Guest]: debates on who the next chief justice is going to be so all of this is we are looking at

00:53:44.120 --> 00:53:49.800
[Guest]: these one two three places for us to get manners from heaven and to get solutions from them

00:53:49.800 --> 00:53:53.400
[Guest]: all of this can only happen if there are these myriad struggles that are constantly pushing

00:53:53.400 --> 00:53:59.000
[Guest]: these institutions to answer and many more people who are willing from the political

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:05.320
[Guest]: opposition to not say Lakshmi and Ganesh on the vote but to actually say we are prepared

00:54:05.320 --> 00:54:11.060
[Guest]: to go to jail and let's flood our jails with the opposition doesn't matter if you want

00:54:11.060 --> 00:54:14.800
[Guest]: to do it but we are going to raise some inconvenient questions we are going to raise questions

00:54:14.800 --> 00:54:19.280
[Guest]: of the lynching of minorities the lynching of Dalits the attacks on girls in Uttar Pradesh

00:54:19.280 --> 00:54:24.720
[Guest]: we are going to raise these issues even if it's inconvenient so there is a sense of despair

00:54:24.720 --> 00:54:31.320
[Guest]: because of the quiet we see but I think we need to start looking for constructive noise

00:54:31.320 --> 00:54:36.760
[Amit Varma]: and constructive struggles so we will talk about each of these one by one as we go along

00:54:36.760 --> 00:54:41.800
[Amit Varma]: in the conversation but first there is a book by Rohit Dey called the People's Constitution

00:54:41.800 --> 00:54:46.360
[Amit Varma]: which makes exactly that point that these are not just imported values these are lived

00:54:46.360 --> 00:54:52.720
[Amit Varma]: values and they reflect in people's struggles in different ways let me ask you sort of my

00:54:52.720 --> 00:54:57.520
[Amit Varma]: final digressive question before we get back to our chronological narrative of your growing

00:54:57.520 --> 00:55:02.800
[Amit Varma]: up and your family and all of that and this one nicely segues into that because you know

00:55:02.800 --> 00:55:08.040
[Amit Varma]: you said a little earlier that you were almost sort of the ninth lawyer in the family down

00:55:08.040 --> 00:55:15.640
[Amit Varma]: the family line and all of that and it would seem to me that in one way you are doing exactly

00:55:15.640 --> 00:55:20.760
[Amit Varma]: the same thing or working in exactly the same spirit as your grandfather and as his father

00:55:20.760 --> 00:55:27.720
[Amit Varma]: before him in the sense that they were using their skills to work for a better society

00:55:27.720 --> 00:55:33.920
[Amit Varma]: in the role that most made sense to them at the time right so flush after independence

00:55:33.920 --> 00:55:39.240
[Amit Varma]: for example your granddad M.C. Settlebarth first attorney general it would have seemed

00:55:39.240 --> 00:55:45.480
[Amit Varma]: that yeah I know the law this is independent India needs people like me and that is what

00:55:45.480 --> 00:55:52.600
[Amit Varma]: an idealist would do and we find over time that that idealism and that hope in the in

00:55:52.600 --> 00:55:59.120
[Amit Varma]: the virtues of the state have kind of vanished that we are faced with a much starker reality

00:55:59.120 --> 00:56:03.000
[Amit Varma]: and it might and and you would obviously you don't know whether it's true or not but I

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:07.080
[Amit Varma]: imagine if your grandfather was born when you were he might have gone down on the kind

00:56:07.080 --> 00:56:13.960
[Amit Varma]: of line that you did because you can't anymore make a better society in that way from within

00:56:13.960 --> 00:56:20.480
[Amit Varma]: the system because it'll just corrode you and it'll eat you up and in a sense if you

00:56:20.480 --> 00:56:28.400
[Amit Varma]: you know want to go down those paths you end up like your root in that sense feels natural

00:56:28.400 --> 00:56:33.280
[Amit Varma]: like on one hand and and and that's you know a separate side question that how do we become

00:56:33.280 --> 00:56:38.200
[Amit Varma]: what we become how much of it is contingent and how much of it is has something to do

00:56:38.200 --> 00:56:43.680
[Amit Varma]: with our essential nature and on the one hand it might seem contingent different things

00:56:43.680 --> 00:56:47.760
[Amit Varma]: happen you know your first journalism job you're covering those riots you're covering

00:56:47.760 --> 00:56:52.680
[Amit Varma]: criminal violence on one hand it might seem contingent but on the other hand in these

00:56:52.680 --> 00:56:58.120
[Amit Varma]: times what else could you have been is another question that comes to my mind yeah actually

00:56:58.120 --> 00:57:02.920
[Guest]: that's interesting this I was just rereading my grandfather's autobiography my life law

00:57:02.920 --> 00:57:08.040
[Guest]: and other things and there's a very interesting chapter in it on the Mundra scandal which

00:57:08.040 --> 00:57:14.080
[Guest]: was the independent India's first huge financial scam and scandal and he was Attorney General

00:57:14.080 --> 00:57:20.320
[Guest]: at the time and the fact that and the whole question of autonomy of autonomy of opposition

00:57:20.320 --> 00:57:23.640
[Guest]: if I look at today with the Attorney General I mean today we have a very decent Attorney

00:57:23.640 --> 00:57:28.240
[Guest]: General after many years but look at how the Solicitor General is functioning today it's

00:57:28.240 --> 00:57:32.040
[Guest]: so crude you know apart from anything and so it tells you a little bit about how these

00:57:32.040 --> 00:57:39.680
[Guest]: institutions need to function because he narrates it was the Chagla MC Chagla the Doan was appointed

00:57:39.680 --> 00:57:44.120
[Guest]: as Commissioner into the scandal and he was representing the government government as

00:57:44.120 --> 00:57:48.480
[Guest]: in state not in government in power so he and he had made that very clear and the entire

00:57:48.480 --> 00:57:52.560
[Guest]: proceedings were in our city which is the old town hall where now the Director General

00:57:52.560 --> 00:57:57.480
[Guest]: of Police sits and it was hugely attended by the public Chagla had taken the decision

00:57:57.480 --> 00:58:01.440
[Guest]: that it'll be open and of course Settelbad was arguing and that all these evidence was

00:58:01.440 --> 00:58:06.280
[Guest]: coming etc and the very interesting passages from there because obviously the dispensation

00:58:06.280 --> 00:58:13.400
[Guest]: and that was our first Prime Minister highly regarded and it was about the LIC scam LIC

00:58:13.400 --> 00:58:19.560
[Guest]: investing out of turn more than a crore of its capital on in private enterprise when

00:58:19.560 --> 00:58:24.360
[Guest]: it should could not have done that without under the act under which it was formed and

00:58:24.360 --> 00:58:29.840
[Guest]: without consulting its shareholders which is the public so anyway so of course the stand

00:58:29.840 --> 00:58:34.280
[Guest]: that my grandfather took and then the praise he got from the newspapers and all of that

00:58:34.280 --> 00:58:39.560
[Guest]: and obviously dispensation was not happy and including the Prime Minister was not very

00:58:39.560 --> 00:58:44.400
[Guest]: happy with the kind of independence stand he took yet after the whole thing got over

00:58:44.400 --> 00:58:50.040
[Guest]: and the T Krishnamachari was compelled to resign after the Finance Minister so it was

00:58:50.040 --> 00:58:54.920
[Guest]: like a huge thing internationally as well he described the first visit to the prior

00:58:54.920 --> 00:58:58.960
[Guest]: Nehru's residence after dinner because there were a lot of rumors that now Settelbad will

00:58:58.960 --> 00:59:05.000
[Guest]: resign because he was Attorney General for about 12 years because the government is unhappy

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:08.960
[Guest]: with him and I think Nehru went out of his way apart from anything else to say that that

00:59:08.960 --> 00:59:14.280
[Guest]: is not what he intended at all though he was upset at the time so it's both things you

00:59:14.280 --> 00:59:18.600
[Guest]: see you see the fact that yes there was this tension and the tension was unfortunate and

00:59:18.600 --> 00:59:23.600
[Guest]: should not have happened that you saw the Finance Secretary and the Home and the Finance

00:59:23.600 --> 00:59:28.000
[Guest]: Minister and the State Bank Chairperson and the RBI Chairperson behaving in ways they

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:33.560
[Guest]: shouldn't have but you equally saw the Attorney General and MC Chagla and others functioning

00:59:33.560 --> 00:59:38.280
[Guest]: above I mean beyond par you know and then he writes there that then you know after that

00:59:38.280 --> 00:59:45.000
[Guest]: he talks about his father Sir Chimanlal Settelbad who my great-grandfather went because he cross

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:50.080
[Guest]: examined Dyer in the Hunter Commission and because of it that but for me it was so important

00:59:50.080 --> 00:59:54.880
[Guest]: also to see about Chimanlal and this I'm hoping that his autobiography we are reprinting now

00:59:54.880 --> 01:00:01.280
[Guest]: my as well because if people demanded but it's out of print is that he was a close colleague

01:00:01.280 --> 01:00:08.560
[Guest]: of Babasaheb Ambedkar and in 1924 Chimanlal was president of what is called the Bahishket

01:00:08.560 --> 01:00:16.520
[Guest]: Hithkarni Sabha which was formed with the aim of ensuring the construction of 124 hostels

01:00:16.520 --> 01:00:20.520
[Guest]: for Dalit girls and boys because the whole understanding being that you know they're

01:00:20.520 --> 01:00:25.280
[Guest]: left out they can't stay there because only residential colleges are possible so we must

01:00:25.280 --> 01:00:30.720
[Guest]: have this and it's not just Chimanlal the entire trust the board of that was one Parsi

01:00:30.720 --> 01:00:36.280
[Guest]: one Jew so different castes and communities recognizing the vision of Ambedkar of course

01:00:36.280 --> 01:00:40.600
[Guest]: this is the tradition one has grown up very proudly with and knew about this but I was

01:00:40.600 --> 01:00:46.280
[Guest]: very personally it was sort of assumed that I would be the one we are just two sisters

01:00:46.280 --> 01:00:49.200
[Guest]: I would be the one who does law because my sister was not particularly interested I was

01:00:49.200 --> 01:00:56.080
[Guest]: always very interested in the law and current affairs and everything but I mean 12th standard

01:00:56.080 --> 01:01:00.120
[Guest]: changed all that 7th standard changed all that when I was about 12 years old when I

01:01:00.120 --> 01:01:04.080
[Guest]: just a book that my father bought me actually all the precedence men and I said no I just

01:01:04.080 --> 01:01:09.320
[Guest]: have to do journalism and I told him that one day in one of our myriad discussions and

01:01:09.320 --> 01:01:14.560
[Guest]: arguments that I want to now do journalism I remember he didn't say a word he didn't

01:01:14.560 --> 01:01:19.000
[Guest]: even say that there was no pressure no pressure at all he just sort of kept quiet for a few

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:23.640
[Guest]: minutes and then he said you have to do what you are most happy doing and I think that

01:01:23.640 --> 01:01:28.680
[Guest]: feeling of being brought up in that sort of environment where you had a father who asked

01:01:28.680 --> 01:01:33.360
[Guest]: him to call him by his first name he never asked us to call him father or papa or daddy

01:01:33.360 --> 01:01:39.040
[Guest]: or whatever we always called him Atul both of us and he was very comfortable with two

01:01:39.040 --> 01:01:44.680
[Guest]: girl children I think my mother probably wanted a son but because there were two miscarriages

01:01:44.680 --> 01:01:49.080
[Guest]: after my younger sister but I don't think he was at all at all concerned that he didn't

01:01:49.080 --> 01:01:55.480
[Guest]: have a son I think this also gets allows a lot of self-confidence to grow so then you

01:01:55.480 --> 01:01:59.520
[Guest]: not only decide to take on a profession which is not this thing but you also ask questions

01:01:59.520 --> 01:02:04.280
[Guest]: of your father who's told you once that don't study your kundra and your history textbook

01:02:04.280 --> 01:02:08.440
[Guest]: read the history from your library that you're lucky enough to have because he had a huge

01:02:08.440 --> 01:02:13.240
[Guest]: personal library of history and stuff then I would ask him but why do you have more Nehru

01:02:13.240 --> 01:02:17.560
[Guest]: and Gandhi and Patel and why don't you have Avinash Ambedkar and Phule moment I was in

01:02:17.560 --> 01:02:22.320
[Guest]: junior college so all that questioning and turning would begin your political my own

01:02:22.320 --> 01:02:27.760
[Guest]: politicization in in Elphinstone College which again I chose because my father and grandfather

01:02:27.760 --> 01:02:32.520
[Guest]: and had gone to that college so there was this thing of always being proud of that tradition

01:02:32.520 --> 01:02:38.480
[Guest]: but also also being quite self-assured about questioning it and taking a different path

01:02:38.480 --> 01:02:42.160
[Guest]: and I think that is also probably comes from that upbringing upbringing but of course you're

01:02:42.160 --> 01:02:50.200
[Guest]: also your own person so even as a reporter I covered the courts immediately after doing

01:02:50.200 --> 01:02:55.280
[Guest]: my university beat and political beat I was very keen on legal reportage and coverage

01:02:55.280 --> 01:03:00.840
[Guest]: legal analysis of judgments so I think there was the attraction of the law and understanding

01:03:00.840 --> 01:03:05.120
[Guest]: it or try to deconstruct it didn't ever go away though of course one was looking at it

01:03:05.120 --> 01:03:12.480
[Guest]: from a different prism than a practicing lawyer you know and but I still will see and maybe

01:03:12.480 --> 01:03:16.800
[Guest]: then you want to ask you something more is that I still have had the good fortune of

01:03:16.800 --> 01:03:24.240
[Guest]: it through my work coming across a wide spectrum of lawyers who are existing in today's much

01:03:24.240 --> 01:03:30.720
[Guest]: more difficult system than it would have been for my grandfather or my father and great

01:03:30.720 --> 01:03:36.040
[Guest]: grandfather also that and we're doing such a fine dignified job of it you know and it

01:03:36.040 --> 01:03:41.720
[Guest]: must be so much harder because we are facing a very viciously reprisal oriented government

01:03:41.720 --> 01:03:48.600
[Guest]: and yet they they just carry on at great personal risk and displaying huge moral courage so

01:03:48.600 --> 01:03:55.040
[Guest]: yeah maybe that's the trajectory I took but I'm so glad that there are lawyers within

01:03:55.040 --> 01:03:59.280
[Guest]: in in our courts whether it is Gujarat High Court whether it is Bombay High Court whether

01:03:59.280 --> 01:04:05.360
[Guest]: it is Delhi Supreme Court who are still there to be able to take up the causes that we all

01:04:05.360 --> 01:04:11.280
[Amit Varma]: of us collectively espouse. What did your father feel of the work that you did like

01:04:11.280 --> 01:04:15.160
[Amit Varma]: you've mentioned that in your book you've spoken about how he'd give you strength before

01:04:15.160 --> 01:04:20.560
[Amit Varma]: he passed in 2010 that he was supportive and all of that but in general as your career

01:04:20.560 --> 01:04:26.600
[Amit Varma]: took the parts that it did you know your 10 years as a full-time journalist 83 to 93 and

01:04:26.600 --> 01:04:33.360
[Amit Varma]: then after the activism kind of happened did all of it feel like this is a natural flow

01:04:33.360 --> 01:04:41.080
[Amit Varma]: of things that this is what she you know this is who she is. He was hugely supportive of

01:04:41.080 --> 01:04:45.880
[Guest]: both me and Javed because both of us worked so much together my partner Javed Anand and

01:04:45.880 --> 01:04:50.760
[Guest]: me very supportive of the work when we decided to quit journalism start formal mainstream

01:04:50.760 --> 01:04:55.720
[Guest]: journalism and start Communalism Combat which was also an iconic magazine for the longest

01:04:55.720 --> 01:05:03.600
[Guest]: time August 93 was our first issue and November 2012 was our last issue now we are online

01:05:03.600 --> 01:05:08.360
[Guest]: he was very supportive but I think there was also a sense that maybe you know worry and

01:05:08.360 --> 01:05:15.200
[Guest]: concern that maybe she's going too far and maybe she's challenging a system which cannot

01:05:15.200 --> 01:05:19.880
[Guest]: stomach so much challenge there was also that sense of concern and fear as he grew older

01:05:19.880 --> 01:05:24.920
[Guest]: he was also sick at the end of it so I think he was also very very worried so I remember

01:05:24.920 --> 01:05:32.840
[Guest]: particularly from June this year to September when I was so wrongfully confined and in jail

01:05:32.840 --> 01:05:35.920
[Guest]: one of the thoughts that used to come in I said that you know I never wanted him to go

01:05:35.920 --> 01:05:41.720
[Guest]: so early but but I'm glad he's not there because I don't think he would have been able to handle

01:05:41.720 --> 01:05:47.040
[Guest]: that you know the way in which I was picked up and the way the vilification has been happening

01:05:47.040 --> 01:05:51.200
[Guest]: would have been really too much for him because he really believed in a different India where

01:05:51.200 --> 01:05:56.920
[Guest]: the system cannot be he really believed that the system and the state cannot be so vile

01:05:56.920 --> 01:06:00.440
[Guest]: and that's how it's become it's vile now so I think that is something which would have

01:06:00.440 --> 01:06:05.680
[Guest]: been at a war within himself because he was from that generation that believed that the

01:06:05.680 --> 01:06:11.720
[Guest]: that the state and the courts and the system will not reach that degenerate you know so

01:06:11.720 --> 01:06:16.200
[Guest]: there's always that thing I keep thinking when I think of him though he was a huge huge

01:06:16.200 --> 01:06:21.200
[Guest]: support I think was also a huge sense of worry he had and that you know where is this going

01:06:21.200 --> 01:06:23.400
[Guest]: to take her.

01:06:23.400 --> 01:06:28.760
[Amit Varma]: You mentioned your your grandfather's encounter with Mr. Nehru and how you know your grandfather

01:06:28.760 --> 01:06:34.360
[Amit Varma]: did the right thing and Nehru did the right thing and they were both in that sense upstanding

01:06:34.360 --> 01:06:40.880
[Amit Varma]: but my sense always has been that you know you might be lucky at a particular point in

01:06:40.880 --> 01:06:45.600
[Amit Varma]: time that you have people of great character but you cannot rely on that a well-designed

01:06:45.600 --> 01:06:50.920
[Amit Varma]: system is a system that will function even if you have the worst possible people in charge

01:06:50.920 --> 01:06:56.760
[Amit Varma]: and it is clear that our system is not a well-designed system it's you know it's too top-heavy too

01:06:56.760 --> 01:07:01.400
[Amit Varma]: much power to the state and sort of in a sense the scales have fallen from our eyes over

01:07:01.400 --> 01:07:06.920
[Amit Varma]: the decades you know my dad was an IAS officer as well and when he speaks about the idealism

01:07:06.920 --> 01:07:12.280
[Amit Varma]: with he and his batchmates all joined and you know I think back on that and I'm like

01:07:12.280 --> 01:07:16.880
[Amit Varma]: you know how could you be so idealistic right and today it's easy to say that in hindsight

01:07:16.880 --> 01:07:22.000
[Amit Varma]: when you've seen what the state has become but the point is that that was never really

01:07:22.000 --> 01:07:28.600
[Amit Varma]: going to last and even in your book all your actions represent a great faith in the rule

01:07:28.600 --> 01:07:34.480
[Amit Varma]: of law a great faith that no justice will be done and we have to keep fighting for it

01:07:34.480 --> 01:07:40.960
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth there are parts including in your book where you seem to show a sort

01:07:40.960 --> 01:07:45.800
[Amit Varma]: of despair about where the system is like I'll quote this bit which I found very resonant

01:07:45.800 --> 01:07:49.880
[Amit Varma]: where you write quote there is a lesson to be learned in the struggle for justice the

01:07:49.880 --> 01:07:54.560
[Amit Varma]: system that loves the status quo tolerates interventions up to a point but appears to

01:07:54.560 --> 01:07:59.640
[Amit Varma]: fall short of delivering radical real or substantive justice the system engages with the survivors

01:07:59.640 --> 01:08:04.280
[Amit Varma]: and defenders in the early years but a shake-up of the status quo demands an exceptional judicial

01:08:04.280 --> 01:08:09.760
[Amit Varma]: mind if survivors and defenders labor on for decades 15 years as we have done if we tried

01:08:09.760 --> 01:08:14.960
[Amit Varma]: and take it beyond the small fry offenders somehow the system to keep us in check makes

01:08:14.960 --> 01:08:21.540
[Amit Varma]: us pay stop code and then you went on to elaborate on this and it just seems to me and I of course

01:08:21.540 --> 01:08:28.440
[Amit Varma]: tend to be too cynical but it just seems to me that that that ultimately all these institutions

01:08:28.440 --> 01:08:33.960
[Amit Varma]: will be co-opted you know because just look at the incentives in play of course the judiciary

01:08:33.960 --> 01:08:39.280
[Amit Varma]: will be co-opted of course the attorney general will be like a lawyer for the party in power

01:08:39.280 --> 01:08:46.040
[Amit Varma]: you know of course all of this will happen everything will kind of crumble and and yet

01:08:46.040 --> 01:08:52.120
[Amit Varma]: you keep fighting and placing your faith in this system and you know you continue that

01:08:52.120 --> 01:09:00.680
[Amit Varma]: journey so tell me a bit about how do you reconcile these two like for your father for

01:09:00.680 --> 01:09:06.360
[Amit Varma]: example was you mentioned that it was sad for him to see that the state could become

01:09:06.360 --> 01:09:13.640
[Amit Varma]: this was so did you see that disillusionment creeping in him did you feel that it hurt

01:09:13.640 --> 01:09:20.520
[Amit Varma]: him that in in some senses you know it's like Santa Claus doesn't exist and and and and

01:09:20.520 --> 01:09:27.800
[Amit Varma]: for you did you also have moments of doubt where you said what is the point it's pointless

01:09:27.800 --> 01:09:35.000
[Amit Varma]: you know like you know how how was that for you see when you're in a struggle and the

01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:41.760
[Guest]: struggle keeps changing forms and needs to also adapt strategies and take new strategies

01:09:41.760 --> 01:09:48.120
[Guest]: it's not always you can't always predict the path that the struggle will take I feel that

01:09:48.120 --> 01:09:50.920
[Guest]: when you're when you're in the midst of the struggle and it's by no means over when it

01:09:50.920 --> 01:10:02.280
[Guest]: comes to me or us none of it is over I think the question is also one of what is the option

01:10:02.280 --> 01:10:06.200
[Guest]: what is the option once you're in the midst of it even if I were to allow myself to think

01:10:06.200 --> 01:10:10.800
[Guest]: what is the point like you said or should I give up is that is that is that an option

01:10:10.800 --> 01:10:19.120
[Guest]: at all because you're not representing only yourself you're not representing only an individual

01:10:19.120 --> 01:10:25.520
[Guest]: maverick attempt it is part of a collective process that has metamorphosed into something

01:10:25.520 --> 01:10:33.000
[Guest]: okay so can you just give it up even if you even if you feel more you're a more real person

01:10:33.000 --> 01:10:38.320
[Guest]: now you're more grounded than when you began in terms of the experience of the system you're

01:10:38.320 --> 01:10:42.960
[Guest]: more cynical even can you afford to give up that that's one question I'm placing on the

01:10:42.960 --> 01:10:49.000
[Guest]: table secondly I think you also realize that there are different ways you can take the

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:55.920
[Guest]: same struggle forward okay which is that yes even if you look at certain aspects of say

01:10:55.920 --> 01:11:02.560
[Guest]: targeted killings and communal violence and the accountability we demanded from the state

01:11:02.560 --> 01:11:07.400
[Guest]: through a battle in the courts which was very rigorously fought and unfortunately was not

01:11:07.400 --> 01:11:12.560
[Guest]: echoed by a political battle by the opposition of the same kind because that that's also

01:11:12.560 --> 01:11:17.320
[Guest]: what I say in my book that when when the battle against proto-fascism gets limited to a battle

01:11:17.320 --> 01:11:22.200
[Guest]: in the courts there is no way you're going to win it okay so that that is also a story

01:11:22.200 --> 01:11:28.200
[Guest]: which needs to be that's also a strand that needs to be explored in our conversation that

01:11:28.200 --> 01:11:34.080
[Guest]: why is the political opposition so wary about looking at some of these tumultuous issues

01:11:34.080 --> 01:11:39.560
[Guest]: as part of election campaign hearing till that happens till we met can that ever happen

01:11:39.560 --> 01:11:44.360
[Guest]: till we metamorphose into that South Africa did happen many many countries we've seen

01:11:44.360 --> 01:11:49.320
[Guest]: those language of electoral politics take the language of a of an emancipatory struggle

01:11:49.320 --> 01:11:54.280
[Guest]: whether it is a question of rights of Adivasis or the rights of minorities or targeted killings

01:11:54.280 --> 01:11:58.720
[Guest]: that's not happened in our country yet even right to education does not figure as an election

01:11:58.720 --> 01:12:04.040
[Guest]: manifest to battle so the issue is not just about these are settled word in the courts

01:12:04.040 --> 01:12:09.000
[Guest]: or whatever it is about the issue the issue is okay you're trying to demand accountability

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:15.240
[Guest]: and transparency in heinous targeted killings based on hate speech and hate violence through

01:12:15.240 --> 01:12:19.800
[Guest]: the courts courts have a certain conservative structure they're not diverse they're not

01:12:19.800 --> 01:12:26.040
[Guest]: accountable they're appointed we all know that they're top-heavy they take too long

01:12:26.040 --> 01:12:32.560
[Guest]: all of that can the battle ever be one only there yet if you look at what happened in

01:12:32.560 --> 01:12:40.160
[Guest]: Gujarat 2002 even now with all the setbacks the kind of convictions we got has unprecedented

01:12:40.160 --> 01:12:46.000
[Guest]: compared to 84, 92, 93, Meerut, Maliana what I'm trying to say is that and the question

01:12:46.000 --> 01:12:51.160
[Guest]: you earlier raised which we didn't fully I didn't fully answer is that you know the post

01:12:51.160 --> 01:12:56.640
[Guest]: independence what this what was expected of the state and what was expected of society

01:12:56.640 --> 01:13:02.060
[Guest]: I think the state did some of it but not enough what this you mentioned about Nehru did the

01:13:02.060 --> 01:13:06.960
[Guest]: decent thing he did a decent thing that one time about Mundrabad if you read Nehru and

01:13:06.960 --> 01:13:10.760
[Guest]: the anonymous column he used to write in the statesman he said that I'm becoming more and

01:13:10.760 --> 01:13:15.640
[Guest]: more dictatorial because there's nobody to question me in my cabinet and he then the

01:13:15.640 --> 01:13:21.160
[Guest]: way he proceeded and you see a certain degeneration and you see whether whether it is inducting

01:13:21.160 --> 01:13:27.560
[Guest]: family or whatever it is and the disrespect for federalism and I think that is the important

01:13:27.560 --> 01:13:32.440
[Guest]: thing about the constitution which again has not been understood that it's a unity but

01:13:32.440 --> 01:13:36.920
[Guest]: federal structure and we are seeing this noise is coming from the south we are seeing DMK

01:13:36.920 --> 01:13:41.360
[Guest]: make that noise in a very considered way we are seeing the Kerala make that noise now

01:13:41.360 --> 01:13:46.360
[Guest]: whether it'll be effective or not but it's a battle it's and eventually we are 75, 76

01:13:46.360 --> 01:13:52.480
[Guest]: years down look at other democracies and how they've evolved is democracy the best way

01:13:52.480 --> 01:13:59.880
[Guest]: even history will tell us that but but it has taken 200, 150 years for capitalist entrenched

01:13:59.880 --> 01:14:05.600
[Guest]: democracies to even get their quote-unquote institutions to a level at which when Trump

01:14:05.600 --> 01:14:10.360
[Guest]: is trying to capture that election which one and a half years back you have election officers

01:14:10.360 --> 01:14:15.360
[Guest]: many of them women saying no the last vote will be counted you know which given America's

01:14:15.360 --> 01:14:18.800
[Guest]: foreign policy is no great deal because they massacred people all over the world but at

01:14:18.800 --> 01:14:23.640
[Guest]: least as far as that institution is concerned it gave me a lot of hope you know so I'm just

01:14:23.640 --> 01:14:31.960
[Guest]: saying that it's a very complex battle that we are fighting it's a battle to deepen the

01:14:31.960 --> 01:14:38.040
[Guest]: institutions of governance of democracy in this country to yet our structure of our society

01:14:38.040 --> 01:14:45.760
[Guest]: and state is very very casteist classist and feudal or we did not allow the structures

01:14:45.760 --> 01:14:54.760
[Guest]: of state to get you know to have representation as they ought to have had from the sections

01:14:54.760 --> 01:14:59.760
[Guest]: that needed the most and deserve it the most in terms of if lived democracy had to come

01:14:59.760 --> 01:15:07.960
[Guest]: in anytime any Dalit intellectual talks about and the issue of Dalit representation in the

01:15:07.960 --> 01:15:13.720
[Guest]: higher judiciary they're shot down but it's a very valid question Dalit representation

01:15:13.720 --> 01:15:19.320
[Guest]: gender representation minority representation why can't we raise it because it's a fact

01:15:19.320 --> 01:15:25.560
[Guest]: that it's only when those representations come that you will have a sense of your responding

01:15:25.560 --> 01:15:28.840
[Guest]: and I don't think it's about just identity politics it should be about workers about

01:15:28.840 --> 01:15:34.760
[Guest]: farmers do we have farmers as judges workers as judges teachers as judges you know it's

01:15:34.760 --> 01:15:39.200
[Guest]: all of these kind of cross intersectionalities that we need to think so I know I've gone

01:15:39.200 --> 01:15:44.240
[Guest]: all over the place but what I'm trying to say is that the battle for accountability and

01:15:44.240 --> 01:15:51.120
[Guest]: transparency the battle for from the state certainly can be more successful in the courts

01:15:51.120 --> 01:15:55.920
[Guest]: if the courts are more accountable and I'm not running away from that question but it

01:15:55.920 --> 01:16:00.440
[Guest]: cannot only be fought there it just cannot only be fought there and when we're looking

01:16:00.440 --> 01:16:05.720
[Guest]: at communal violence or targeted violence against sections of ethnic populations caste

01:16:05.720 --> 01:16:11.000
[Guest]: or community it is a kind of a I mean it's a historical reprisal as the section sees

01:16:11.000 --> 01:16:14.840
[Guest]: it for what happened in partition and and that also shows a lack of understanding of

01:16:14.840 --> 01:16:19.840
[Guest]: history because in partition itself if you look at the map of India and I'm sure you

01:16:19.840 --> 01:16:23.520
[Guest]: if you taught history you do the same thing I'll teach history that way that you know

01:16:23.520 --> 01:16:28.000
[Guest]: you look at it from the east to the west and if you look at the trajectory that maybe in

01:16:28.000 --> 01:16:33.280
[Guest]: Bengal you had no Akali and Hindus were massacred most but in Bihar it was large sections of

01:16:33.280 --> 01:16:38.360
[Guest]: the Muslims and in Punjab it was the Sikhs so it is everybody it is it's three communities

01:16:38.360 --> 01:16:44.680
[Guest]: doing it to each other pretty much playing it out and that demon of communal politics

01:16:44.680 --> 01:16:48.800
[Guest]: that actually sits within all communities and which at one stage you're a majority another

01:16:48.800 --> 01:16:53.760
[Guest]: stage you're a minority is what we need to tackle that that's the hate politics that

01:16:53.760 --> 01:16:57.880
[Guest]: we need to tackle and there's a danger of it becoming majoritarianism when it's Hindu

01:16:57.880 --> 01:17:04.560
[Guest]: were here but equally Islamization in Pakistan or the Buddhist state in Sri Lanka so that

01:17:04.560 --> 01:17:08.480
[Guest]: understanding we need to get among our people which means a strain of rationality and a

01:17:08.480 --> 01:17:15.560
[Guest]: strain of questioning and the right wing the supremacist right wing is better organized

01:17:15.560 --> 01:17:22.320
[Guest]: it's it has had its gold in fact it made it clear when it assassinated Gandhiji and that

01:17:22.320 --> 01:17:25.360
[Guest]: was in fact my the first book I edited I don't know if you've seen it it's called beyond

01:17:25.360 --> 01:17:30.280
[Guest]: doubt because I mean for me it was an eye-opener when Jagan Farnes's book I read in Marathi

01:17:30.280 --> 01:17:38.520
[Guest]: in 1998 where I first as a student of history first his book was called Mahatmanji Akher

01:17:38.520 --> 01:17:43.440
[Guest]: and he first wrote and it was his original work that there were five attempts on Gandhi

01:17:43.440 --> 01:17:47.440
[Guest]: before before the last one that successfully killed him and this is not part of the dominant

01:17:47.440 --> 01:17:51.680
[Guest]: narrative even now I have to keep telling people that did you know that there were six

01:17:51.680 --> 01:17:56.200
[Guest]: attempts totally with a six was successful and in three previous attempts Godse was part

01:17:56.200 --> 01:18:01.200
[Guest]: of it so it was not a spontaneous act it was pretty organized pretty well thought out and

01:18:01.200 --> 01:18:08.400
[Guest]: all of it so I just feel it's all of this coming together let's look at the world the

01:18:08.400 --> 01:18:13.680
[Guest]: world is also going very right has gone very right so it's not just an Indian phenomenon

01:18:13.680 --> 01:18:18.960
[Guest]: there's a grappling all along and so much has to do with economic structures and you

01:18:18.960 --> 01:18:25.920
[Guest]: know the the kind of path of neo-liberalization neo-globalization that the world took which

01:18:25.920 --> 01:18:30.880
[Guest]: is now being questioned at some level if you look at South America and some of the states

01:18:30.880 --> 01:18:35.560
[Guest]: there but have we reached a state where we are questioning it I don't think so because

01:18:35.560 --> 01:18:38.240
[Guest]: if you look at what we are doing with the forest conservation rules what we're looking

01:18:38.240 --> 01:18:42.720
[Guest]: at the kind of model of development so you know for civil rights activists also like

01:18:42.720 --> 01:18:47.400
[Guest]: me we have to develop our understanding of economics and what kind of priorities because

01:18:47.400 --> 01:18:54.200
[Guest]: I'm keen on reaching and discussing with the people who feel today that they are jobless

01:18:54.200 --> 01:19:00.240
[Guest]: and hopeless and therefore they can sit and watch propaganda videos we need to reach those

01:19:00.240 --> 01:19:04.760
[Guest]: people because they are the same people who supported Trump you know it's it's the white

01:19:04.760 --> 01:19:09.760
[Guest]: American workforce that supported Trump and I think if that white American workforce is

01:19:09.760 --> 01:19:14.880
[Guest]: feeling completely isolated and without job I cannot say that we can't speak to them I

01:19:14.880 --> 01:19:19.560
[Guest]: cannot say this this is them it's not a them it's a it's a them which is being pulled there

01:19:19.560 --> 01:19:24.520
[Guest]: because of a certain economic reality you know so it's a huge challenge for all of us

01:19:24.520 --> 01:19:30.120
[Guest]: who are trying to work at the people's level at the struggle level at mass organization

01:19:30.120 --> 01:19:37.080
[Guest]: at building up a political opposition we it we all realize also that we have to work with

01:19:37.080 --> 01:19:41.640
[Guest]: the opposition we've got it's not going to radically change the way we want it to so

01:19:41.640 --> 01:19:46.320
[Guest]: how do we make that happen how do we work with it you know these are all all very complicated

01:19:46.320 --> 01:19:50.920
[Guest]: questions and then it boils down to okay what is your struggle and what is your choice and

01:19:50.920 --> 01:19:54.040
[Guest]: do you stop what you're doing what you're doing and then I think the option is not there

01:19:54.040 --> 01:19:59.720
[Guest]: to stop maybe you take a break take a different path for a little while but I mean for instance

01:19:59.720 --> 01:20:04.360
[Guest]: I just wanted to share that apart from the school program the work we're doing in Assam

01:20:04.360 --> 01:20:07.880
[Guest]: at the moment I don't know if you're aware of it it is looking at the law on citizenship

01:20:07.880 --> 01:20:16.760
[Guest]: and the way it's rendering millions of Indians genuine Indian citizens a civil death because

01:20:16.760 --> 01:20:21.800
[Guest]: that's what it is you suddenly wake up and say that you know Amit is not an Indian Tista

01:20:21.800 --> 01:20:26.120
[Guest]: is not an Indian and then I have to just scramble around putting together documents to prove

01:20:26.120 --> 01:20:29.960
[Guest]: my citizenship which is not even required under the Indian constitution and we have

01:20:29.960 --> 01:20:35.880
[Guest]: a team there CJ my organization has been working there since for the last seven years local

01:20:35.880 --> 01:20:42.840
[Guest]: team diverse gender diverse ethnic diverse working in villages and we're ensuring paralegal

01:20:42.840 --> 01:20:48.040
[Guest]: and legal aid now according to me that's if that's a that's a follow-up trajectory to

01:20:48.040 --> 01:20:52.600
[Guest]: what the kind of work we've done before with targeted violence that you're using the law

01:20:52.600 --> 01:20:59.640
[Guest]: bottom up from the foreigner tribunal level up to the supreme court not just going straight

01:20:59.640 --> 01:21:04.760
[Guest]: when there's an incident of mass violence but this is an everyday annihilation of the

01:21:04.760 --> 01:21:10.040
[Guest]: people you know just rendering them completely non-citizens and I think therefore we it's

01:21:10.040 --> 01:21:16.200
[Guest]: like using your previous expertise in a way where a huge humanitarian crisis is brewing

01:21:16.760 --> 01:21:20.840
[Guest]: and when I was in jail and I found and this is what I like to just share with your viewers that

01:21:20.840 --> 01:21:25.480
[Guest]: for a person who has never been looked at herself as an individual but part of a collective battle

01:21:25.480 --> 01:21:29.480
[Guest]: to feel that the kind of organization building that my CJP has done and that we have now

01:21:29.480 --> 01:21:34.360
[Guest]: teams working in Assam we have a team working in Purvanchal and we keep telling our supporters that

01:21:34.360 --> 01:21:40.120
[Guest]: you know these are the teams we need to support it's not a thista or a individual but human rights

01:21:40.120 --> 01:21:46.040
[Guest]: workers and peace workers on the ground who are able to take up these little and bigger challenges

01:21:46.040 --> 01:21:52.520
[Amit Varma]: and that's when the change will happen. So I share your lament about the one point of failure in all

01:21:52.520 --> 01:21:57.720
[Amit Varma]: this which is politics which is the opposition right and my question is about that now this

01:21:57.720 --> 01:22:02.680
[Amit Varma]: this seems to be an assumption on the part of all the opposition parties

01:22:02.680 --> 01:22:09.080
[Amit Varma]: that you cannot mess with the Hindu vote so in some way or the other they will try to you know

01:22:09.080 --> 01:22:14.040
[Amit Varma]: cater to it maybe in the very crude ways that Kejriwal is doing that you put pictures of

01:22:14.040 --> 01:22:19.480
[Amit Varma]: goddesses on banknotes or even earlier when the Babri Masjid judgment came you know Priyanka Gandhi

01:22:19.480 --> 01:22:25.400
[Amit Varma]: boasted that hey my father opened the gates of the Babri Masjid there is this sense that you

01:22:25.400 --> 01:22:31.960
[Amit Varma]: have to in some way show religiosity and so on and they seem to be making the assumption that ties

01:22:31.960 --> 01:22:38.280
[Amit Varma]: in with my sort of pessimistic speculation earlier that this is what society is like politics has

01:22:38.280 --> 01:22:44.200
[Amit Varma]: caught up with it and they seem to be treating it as a non-negotiable now is it the case that they

01:22:44.200 --> 01:22:50.760
[Amit Varma]: are on to something or is it the case that there is a lack of imagination there that there are

01:22:50.760 --> 01:22:56.600
[Amit Varma]: other margins on which you can appeal to people it's you know we all contain multitudes even if

01:22:56.600 --> 01:23:02.520
[Amit Varma]: even if it is the case that religiosity matters even if it is a case that there is a certain

01:23:02.520 --> 01:23:09.480
[Amit Varma]: shared bigotry there there are surely other margins that you can also appeal on and you know

01:23:09.480 --> 01:23:15.480
[Amit Varma]: but this is a battle everyone's just turned their back on so you know so it's that why which I'm

01:23:15.480 --> 01:23:23.000
[Amit Varma]: trying to understand that are our parties are these opposition parties on to something about

01:23:23.000 --> 01:23:29.800
[Amit Varma]: our society which you know may give you and I this quiet and we may not want to accept it or

01:23:29.800 --> 01:23:35.800
[Amit Varma]: are they just showing a lack of imagination that there is a space to fight extraordinarily

01:23:35.800 --> 01:23:41.960
[Guest]: important question you know I can't tell you how important it is and I'll try and just do some

01:23:41.960 --> 01:23:47.880
[Guest]: justice to it see I you know it boils down again to this I mean I like the way you put it that is

01:23:47.880 --> 01:23:53.160
[Guest]: there a lack of imagination I think there is a lack of imagination if I believe as a as a Rahul

01:23:53.160 --> 01:23:59.560
[Guest]: Gandhi or a Krijiwal or a Mamata or whatever if I believe that this is where society is that this is

01:23:59.560 --> 01:24:05.880
[Guest]: there's actually everybody has now always been or has become so divided and so polarized that that's

01:24:05.880 --> 01:24:13.000
[Guest]: the only language I can speak then I will keep perpetuating this lack of imagine but if I actually

01:24:13.000 --> 01:24:19.960
[Guest]: and I think that's the other problem that if you look at the election figures of number of people

01:24:19.960 --> 01:24:25.880
[Guest]: who don't vote I think that's a figure that really important to look at it tells a very

01:24:25.880 --> 01:24:30.360
[Guest]: despairing tale it means a lot of people are just so disillusioned with what's being offered it's

01:24:30.360 --> 01:24:34.600
[Guest]: not that they're going to this or that they just seem we don't want to vote okay then if you put

01:24:34.600 --> 01:24:38.520
[Guest]: it together with those who are not voting for this regime I think the figure is pretty large

01:24:38.520 --> 01:24:45.400
[Guest]: pretty large so I think it's lack of imagination to first say that it's lack of imagination and

01:24:45.400 --> 01:24:51.000
[Guest]: that lack of imagination is not simply from what the way you put it that go to other issues I think

01:24:51.000 --> 01:24:55.880
[Guest]: the other issues must be gone too whether it's unemployment or prices and all but I think it's

01:24:55.880 --> 01:25:01.720
[Guest]: also about tackling diversity and secularism head-on and there I want to hark on something

01:25:01.720 --> 01:25:05.960
[Guest]: which is something that people don't want to talk about which is that how did Javed and I start the

01:25:05.960 --> 01:25:13.160
[Guest]: work we did from about 1986 onwards 93 we began combat formally but actually this whole turning

01:25:13.160 --> 01:25:19.320
[Guest]: began in around 1986 I don't even know you were born then but it was a very incredibly

01:25:19.320 --> 01:25:25.320
[Guest]: critical period for India I was a teenager then I'm just joking thank you for that

01:25:26.360 --> 01:25:31.080
[Guest]: very critical period for India very critical period for India because you saw so many things

01:25:31.080 --> 01:25:39.880
[Guest]: happening at the same time and if I just want to encapsulate those two three were one was of

01:25:39.880 --> 01:25:45.960
[Guest]: course we you you referred to it opening what Priyanka said opening of the talas of the Babri

01:25:45.960 --> 01:25:54.280
[Guest]: Masjid but not as as important was the reaction of the Muslim male clergy to the Shabano judgment

01:25:54.280 --> 01:26:00.600
[Guest]: okay now this was within weeks of each other both happening within weeks of each other and we saw

01:26:00.600 --> 01:26:08.520
[Guest]: as young journalists we saw that what awful effect it was having on the ground because the VHP

01:26:09.160 --> 01:26:14.680
[Guest]: VHP had made this the Babri the construction of the Ram Mandir their program from 86 onwards

01:26:15.880 --> 01:26:21.400
[Guest]: BJP adopted it a year or two later but the Shabanu judgment was like a manner from heaven for the

01:26:21.400 --> 01:26:27.400
[Guest]: right for the Hindutva right because the manner in which not just the Muslim male clergy reacted

01:26:27.400 --> 01:26:32.920
[Guest]: but the manner in which India's centrist party reacted which is the congress was was horrendous

01:26:33.800 --> 01:26:38.040
[Guest]: instead of negotiating and navigating with the vast majority of India's Muslims

01:26:38.760 --> 01:26:43.960
[Guest]: which includes its women you know they were negotiating with just a top heavy clergy

01:26:43.960 --> 01:26:48.680
[Guest]: and the response they were getting in terms of the shouting and the hordes and the slogan

01:26:48.680 --> 01:26:54.840
[Guest]: hearing was confirmed to that middle road a Hindu who had not gone over to that side

01:26:54.840 --> 01:26:59.560
[Guest]: that yes this is a section that wants special treatment under the law and wants is not even

01:26:59.560 --> 01:27:04.840
[Guest]: prepared to give 125 rupees for an old woman who's been divorced what does this mean you saw

01:27:04.840 --> 01:27:11.720
[Guest]: minority communalism feeding into majority communalism exactly what led me to do so much

01:27:11.720 --> 01:27:17.400
[Guest]: reading of my history pre-partition and I teach it now in the class to the 8, 9, 10 standards junior

01:27:17.400 --> 01:27:25.160
[Guest]: colleges that we have to understand the trajectory of this country between 1857 1847 to 1933 and then

01:27:25.160 --> 01:27:35.960
[Guest]: 1947 why till 1925 did you not see the emergence of these sectarian forces from both sides and then

01:27:35.960 --> 01:27:42.360
[Guest]: what happens between 1925 and 1937 when you first have the Muslim League pass up a Lahore resolution

01:27:42.360 --> 01:27:49.880
[Guest]: you know to believe for anybody to any critical thinker in India to believe that secularism can

01:27:49.880 --> 01:27:58.360
[Guest]: only be two things that secularism can only be a battle to for Hindus to become liberal and to

01:27:58.360 --> 01:28:03.640
[Guest]: Hindus to battle caste and that minority should not be touched I think it's not to understand

01:28:03.640 --> 01:28:10.040
[Guest]: what secularization of society means number one and I think number two is not to understand that

01:28:10.040 --> 01:28:15.800
[Guest]: historically this has always played up that minority communalism has played into majority

01:28:15.800 --> 01:28:20.600
[Guest]: communalism and whereas of course I agree with Nehru when he said that majority communalism is

01:28:20.600 --> 01:28:26.680
[Guest]: endangers the state because the structure of the state changes what happens to society when minority

01:28:26.680 --> 01:28:31.560
[Guest]: communalism is given a free hand and is not tackled is that it's three or four things first of all you

01:28:31.560 --> 01:28:37.080
[Guest]: don't give agency to the moderate liberal dissenting voices among Muslims you don't allow that

01:28:37.080 --> 01:28:42.600
[Guest]: you don't allow that leadership to emerge and you ignore the Muslim women completely you know

01:28:42.600 --> 01:28:46.920
[Guest]: and can you imagine something more horrific than the fact that it's under this regime that an issue

01:28:46.920 --> 01:28:51.800
[Guest]: like talaq is raised when organizations like the Indian Muslim for Secular Democracy which my husband

01:28:52.360 --> 01:28:59.160
[Guest]: partner represents has been talking against triple talaq polygamy and halal for like two decades

01:28:59.960 --> 01:29:05.320
[Guest]: and yet you know the it's just completely ignored by mainstream politicians so this lack of

01:29:05.320 --> 01:29:11.320
[Guest]: imagination encompasses even this that what is secularism secularism is not about giving Friday

01:29:11.320 --> 01:29:17.080
[Guest]: holidays to Muslims or to give the prophets birthday as a holiday to Muslims that's not what

01:29:17.080 --> 01:29:22.440
[Guest]: the vast majority of Indian Muslims have ever wanted it's like an insult to them the vast

01:29:22.440 --> 01:29:30.200
[Guest]: majority of Muslims in this country are working class artisans craftsmen self-made people and

01:29:30.200 --> 01:29:35.960
[Guest]: they're from the subaltern caste they're not from the Ashraf Syed caste who've been the leadership

01:29:35.960 --> 01:29:42.600
[Guest]: of the opposition parties they have been asking for their share in the economic social cake even

01:29:42.600 --> 01:29:48.760
[Guest]: within the community they haven't got it so I think if if political parties started articulating

01:29:48.760 --> 01:29:56.120
[Guest]: what India stands for in terms of all of this secularism means this secularism

01:29:56.120 --> 01:30:05.400
[Guest]: equality non-discrimination between various faiths and within communities as well I think

01:30:05.400 --> 01:30:10.200
[Guest]: if you have the moral courage to do that and I can't see which leaders are very few there are a

01:30:10.200 --> 01:30:18.120
[Guest]: few who do it in their own way I think it's it's possible that your disgruntled

01:30:19.160 --> 01:30:24.520
[Guest]: hassle voter who doesn't vote will get inspired to say yes we believe we are like Muslims who

01:30:24.520 --> 01:30:29.640
[Guest]: are secular we are Hindus or secular but we don't want this nonsense kind of secularism that you're

01:30:29.640 --> 01:30:35.480
[Guest]: electorally peddling out to us which is meaningless we want real secularism and I think the real

01:30:35.480 --> 01:30:41.560
[Guest]: secularism exists it's it's morally people are living it all the time Muslims have I mean if you

01:30:41.560 --> 01:30:46.120
[Guest]: look at today's Muslim you look at the number of Muslim girls who are kind of educating themselves

01:30:46.120 --> 01:30:50.040
[Guest]: they've not done it on a free lunch they've done it out of the battling patriarchy within the

01:30:50.040 --> 01:30:55.160
[Guest]: battling patriarchy within the families but they just need articulation why is opposition

01:30:55.160 --> 01:31:01.240
[Guest]: politics not keen on doing that and I think it's possible to do that it needs to and these

01:31:01.240 --> 01:31:07.880
[Guest]: things need to be said I mean when someone like Tikayat the farmers leader in Muzaffarnagar

01:31:09.960 --> 01:31:15.960
[Guest]: has that slogan Har Har Mahavadev Allahu Akbar it's a transformational moment

01:31:15.960 --> 01:31:22.120
[Guest]: because all of us are wondering Rakesh Tikayat used to be a fairly reactionary big big farmer

01:31:22.120 --> 01:31:26.760
[Guest]: but even that whole struggle and his interacting with the small farmer the middle farmer the woman

01:31:26.760 --> 01:31:32.600
[Guest]: farmer the Dalit farmer and his realization that where is this politics taking us has made him kind

01:31:32.600 --> 01:31:37.880
[Guest]: of utter those slogans you know even Mamata Banerjee when she was faced with a couple of

01:31:37.880 --> 01:31:42.360
[Guest]: times during the Bengal elections she was trying to articulate Ishwar Allah Tero Nam this is my

01:31:42.360 --> 01:31:48.200
[Guest]: secularism don't try and tell me when the I think the congress on the left hand try and put up an

01:31:48.200 --> 01:31:53.080
