02:25:48.520 --> 02:25:57.000
[Amit Varma]: barrage of sensation and information just kind of coming at you and one thing that i keep reminding

02:25:57.000 --> 02:26:02.840
[Amit Varma]: myself to do is to fight this that don't look into your phone when you know when you're with

02:26:02.840 --> 02:26:09.720
[Amit Varma]: someone that make an effort to you know to be with your friends and all of that so do you have

02:26:09.720 --> 02:26:15.800
[Amit Varma]: do you have any observations about this because one of the things that you've done through your

02:26:15.800 --> 02:26:24.200
[Amit Varma]: activism is stayed in touch with people actual people you actually meet them actual conversations

02:26:24.200 --> 02:26:29.960
[Amit Varma]: phone calls instead of whatsapp messages you know one very powerful part of your book and we'll come

02:26:29.960 --> 02:26:35.720
[Amit Varma]: to that when we speak about 2002 is when as events unfolded you got call after call after call after

02:26:35.720 --> 02:26:43.160
[Amit Varma]: call after call tell me a little bit about this you know this changing texture of life as it

02:26:43.960 --> 02:26:47.800
[Amit Varma]: as it were and is it something that you've noticed that you feel you need to be on the

02:26:47.800 --> 02:26:52.840
[Amit Varma]: watch out for or that you've seen affecting people around you because i would imagine

02:26:52.840 --> 02:26:58.200
[Amit Varma]: that your kids would have had really different childhoods or growing up years and what someone

02:26:58.200 --> 02:27:04.600
[Guest]: like you would have just in terms of experiences yes and no i think both you're right that you

02:27:04.600 --> 02:27:14.600
[Guest]: know the sheer barrage of electronic information or electronic disinformation that is kind of

02:27:14.600 --> 02:27:19.960
[Guest]: thrown at us is just it's just so it's from all over the place so it's like very difficult to

02:27:19.960 --> 02:27:24.600
[Guest]: escape it but i think and you have to fight it you have to fight it for sure but i think

02:27:24.600 --> 02:27:29.880
[Guest]: some of us our lives inevitably become the fight itself because in for instance

02:27:29.880 --> 02:27:35.800
[Guest]: um there's no way i can do my work without actually engaging with actual people which

02:27:35.800 --> 02:27:41.720
[Guest]: means lots and lots of very very good conversations also means fighting for that time to have those

02:27:41.720 --> 02:27:47.080
[Guest]: conversations because sometimes the other work also takes over which is writing and communicating

02:27:47.080 --> 02:27:53.240
[Guest]: and all of that and everything but i think the sheer activism the sheer expanse of this

02:27:53.240 --> 02:27:56.680
[Guest]: activism means that you have to actually be engaging so you've already said that

02:27:56.680 --> 02:28:01.800
[Guest]: but i think uh uh on a lighter note you know you just have to go to jail to realize

02:28:02.600 --> 02:28:06.840
[Guest]: what happens when your phone is not there or you don't have a device because then the then it's

02:28:06.840 --> 02:28:10.680
[Guest]: it's very and then it's back to your books i mean if you can manage to get the books it's only the

02:28:10.680 --> 02:28:18.360
[Guest]: books and only the books but uh it's uh it's it's one great thing that happened because like you

02:28:18.360 --> 02:28:24.040
[Guest]: yourself mentioned that except for four years i've been here is our kids also grew up here so i was

02:28:24.040 --> 02:28:31.480
[Guest]: very very clear about this that there was no question of unregulated television or computer

02:28:31.480 --> 02:28:37.480
[Guest]: even so they were just on the in the garden and on the beach most of the time so apart from school

02:28:37.480 --> 02:28:44.440
[Guest]: which was bad enough for or good enough or whatever so it it was both being in the modern world and

02:28:44.440 --> 02:28:48.120
[Guest]: yet being quite different because you had the lucky enough to have the outdoors so i think that

02:28:48.120 --> 02:28:54.680
[Guest]: was a good balancing act that happened and then there was very kind of that you choose maybe one

02:28:54.680 --> 02:28:59.800
[Guest]: or two programs for two hours a week and that's it nothing more but that also meant that we did

02:28:59.800 --> 02:29:04.760
[Guest]: not have the television on and that was a very clear choice that we made though we were journalists

02:29:04.760 --> 02:29:09.240
[Guest]: though we were activists stroke news persons we said whatever we do is after they sleep because

02:29:09.240 --> 02:29:13.640
[Guest]: you can't have it running and then make that choice for them it has to be for all of us so

02:29:13.640 --> 02:29:19.880
[Guest]: these are things that you need to be able to be clear clear about you know when you're parenting

02:29:19.880 --> 02:29:25.800
[Guest]: as well but yes it is true that but fortunately i'm i'm quite a crazy i'm crazy person in the

02:29:25.800 --> 02:29:31.080
[Guest]: sense i love cooking i love working with my hands i love craft i love gardening so if i don't do

02:29:31.080 --> 02:29:36.280
[Guest]: that i'll go crazy so because of all of that then that is non-digital work that's non-phone work so

02:29:36.280 --> 02:29:42.760
[Guest]: i can't do without all of that so and i am i've been lucky enough to have really really good

02:29:42.760 --> 02:29:48.760
[Guest]: friends both from childhood and college and even through my activism where new friends have come

02:29:48.760 --> 02:29:53.240
[Guest]: and they're as solid as the old ones and for me the greatest joy when i was in jail was receiving

02:29:53.240 --> 02:29:59.880
[Guest]: 2700 postcards and letters which i was just i mean that just i think if there's one thing that kept

02:29:59.880 --> 02:30:04.760
[Guest]: me going apart from visits from my family it was that and i think it was started as a political

02:30:04.760 --> 02:30:10.280
[Guest]: act by the union the adivasi union i'm working with and the Janwadi Mahila Andolan which is the

02:30:10.280 --> 02:30:15.160
[Guest]: women's wing of the cpim but then it took different form because i got so many personal letters

02:30:16.040 --> 02:30:22.040
[Guest]: childhood friends from california who are now in california or a journalist from indian express

02:30:22.040 --> 02:30:27.320
[Guest]: who wrote to me we worked together in 86 she walks to a card shop in birmingham buys the card

02:30:27.320 --> 02:30:32.440
[Guest]: and posts it to the sabarmati women's jail you know i mean these are i mean i even now it's like

02:30:32.440 --> 02:30:36.920
[Guest]: even now it's like one and a half months down that i'm out but i read and read them all the

02:30:36.920 --> 02:30:41.880
[Guest]: time because i think when and i realize also the importance of the pen and the written word it's

02:30:41.880 --> 02:30:46.920
[Guest]: not simply so i i've told myself that before the year is out i'm going to be replying to each one

02:30:46.920 --> 02:30:51.000
[Guest]: of them so and that that's that's the task i've set myself because i think it's very important

02:30:51.000 --> 02:30:56.520
[Guest]: to write letters back and not just email or whatsapp letters back and i think so these i

02:30:56.520 --> 02:31:01.720
[Guest]: think because i think it's the handwriting the pen the paper the postcard the picture postcard

02:31:01.720 --> 02:31:05.800
[Guest]: some of them that they sent and the words that they wrote i mean a close friend of mine jerry

02:31:05.800 --> 02:31:12.040
[Guest]: pinto uh author he wrote one the first postcard which is a picture postcard which has a stamp of

02:31:12.040 --> 02:31:16.200
[Guest]: jay prakash narayan and gandhi where he said they also spent a lot of time in jail and they're

02:31:16.200 --> 02:31:21.960
[Guest]: thinking of you all the time and then there were 16 more which were poems which were unsigned

02:31:21.960 --> 02:31:26.040
[Guest]: and i'm telling myself this is the same person and it was i didn't connect that this is jerry

02:31:26.040 --> 02:31:31.720
[Guest]: he wrote poems from different people from palestinian poets to japanese sports all resistance

02:31:31.720 --> 02:31:37.000
[Guest]: poetry and he wrote poem number one poem number two and poem number 16 and each one was a beautiful

02:31:37.000 --> 02:31:41.880
[Guest]: poetry so i mean such lovely stuff people did you know when you were inside and i think these were

02:31:41.880 --> 02:31:47.080
[Amit Varma]: the these were the things that really kept one going yeah i i think the only thing of value we

02:31:47.080 --> 02:31:54.040
[Amit Varma]: collect are people and and this is such a beautiful story in your memoir you also speak about how

02:31:54.040 --> 02:31:57.960
[Amit Varma]: you wrote letters and cards to your grandparents and you were encouraged to do so and you just

02:31:57.960 --> 02:32:04.760
[Amit Varma]: mentioned writing again and something that i often think about is that the experience of writing

02:32:04.760 --> 02:32:09.880
[Amit Varma]: letters and notes and messages has changed completely in the sense that today everything

02:32:09.880 --> 02:32:15.880
[Amit Varma]: is a whatsapp message or a quick email or whatever it's very functional it's very brief

02:32:15.880 --> 02:32:23.160
[Amit Varma]: whereas back in the day if he sat down to write to someone the act of writing itself was one it

02:32:23.160 --> 02:32:27.160
[Amit Varma]: was communicating to the other person that i care about you i'm spending time on this

02:32:27.160 --> 02:32:32.120
[Amit Varma]: and two it was an act of actually sitting down with yourself and examining the contents of your

02:32:32.120 --> 02:32:37.400
[Amit Varma]: own mind it's a it's like a deliberate act of consideration it's not just that you hit compose

02:32:37.400 --> 02:32:43.720
[Amit Varma]: on gmail and you say you know are you free at eight or whatever you know so and and you mentioned

02:32:43.720 --> 02:32:48.600
[Amit Varma]: that you'd like to do that and you mentioned what it meant for you to receive all of that and it's

02:32:48.600 --> 02:32:56.360
[Amit Varma]: hard to sort of look back and kind of try to reconstruct this or whatever but how important

02:32:56.360 --> 02:33:06.120
[Amit Varma]: do you feel things like that were in sort of shaping the way you related to people understanding

02:33:06.120 --> 02:33:11.480
[Amit Varma]: yourself because every time you sit down to write something you you you get to know yourself a little

02:33:11.480 --> 02:33:17.960
[Amit Varma]: bit a bit better in that act so how important was that kind of writing to you and do you feel that

02:33:17.960 --> 02:33:22.760
[Amit Varma]: you lost like when now when you say that i like to do more of it is it because you stopped and

02:33:22.760 --> 02:33:30.200
[Guest]: didn't do enough of it at some point and you feel that it would help you know i like to kind of make

02:33:30.200 --> 02:33:34.600
[Guest]: two comparisons one to your earlier earlier question and this one that there's something

02:33:34.600 --> 02:33:40.600
[Guest]: very very similar between the art of conversation and the art of letter writing and i was very lucky

02:33:40.600 --> 02:33:47.000
[Guest]: to grow up with fine conversationalists so i mean whether it's my father or my grandfather

02:33:47.000 --> 02:33:53.560
[Guest]: or another person who was very close to us H.M. Sirvai who was my father's senior and his son

02:33:53.560 --> 02:34:00.440
[Guest]: Navrose Sirvai who continues to be a very dear friend there was joy in conversation so and that

02:34:00.440 --> 02:34:08.360
[Guest]: conversation was personal political books poetry all of it intertwined so you realize that the time

02:34:08.360 --> 02:34:16.200
[Guest]: you spend together with such people and my father spent a lot of time with his chambermates what's

02:34:16.200 --> 02:34:21.880
[Guest]: lawyers call their chambermates so the parties for juniors were like big occasions for us because

02:34:21.880 --> 02:34:27.000
[Guest]: not only would a lot of good food be planned but there would be lots of very lively conversation

02:34:27.000 --> 02:34:34.600
[Guest]: so all the family friends we had all the chamber friends we had conversations were very important

02:34:34.600 --> 02:34:40.840
[Guest]: and these were not conversations about Shadi and Bihar and Dowry but they were conversations about

02:34:40.840 --> 02:34:46.360
[Guest]: life about what was happening around the emergency i mean the emergency was a huge thing

02:34:46.360 --> 02:34:52.680
[Guest]: in our childhood you know i've written about it also but i mean for me it was a formative moment

02:34:52.680 --> 02:34:59.720
[Guest]: when i'm in standard 10 in 77 when the elections are called and you have your parents both telling

02:34:59.720 --> 02:35:06.280
[Guest]: you that listen your studies are not as important as your campaigning to get this government out

02:35:06.280 --> 02:35:11.480
[Guest]: and you know in the pre-emergency in sorry in the pre-election period during the emergency

02:35:12.040 --> 02:35:18.520
[Guest]: it was the homes of the Settlewad and the Chaglas and the Bhatkals in Bombay that all these meetings

02:35:18.520 --> 02:35:22.520
[Guest]: would take place as to how the Janata party can come back and we need to get this government out

02:35:22.520 --> 02:35:29.480
[Guest]: and etc so you know that that's a heavy dose of life and politicization that happens and then

02:35:29.480 --> 02:35:36.440
[Guest]: you're out by public transport going to the Bhatkals place in Prabhadevi picking up posters

02:35:36.440 --> 02:35:42.120
[Guest]: and plastering posters all over town and the matter of great pride that Bombay returns six

02:35:42.120 --> 02:35:47.320
[Guest]: seats to the Janata party you know that so that sort of thing now these things don't happen just

02:35:47.320 --> 02:35:52.920
[Guest]: like that they happen as a lot of conversation my first letter to the editor in the India Today

02:35:52.920 --> 02:35:59.800
[Guest]: today was about Indira Gandhi's growing authoritarianism in 1978 and stuff like that

02:35:59.800 --> 02:36:06.200
[Guest]: so you know all of this is so much part of the same thing that you're thinking you're conversing

02:36:06.200 --> 02:36:11.160
[Guest]: you're learning through those conversations you have the benefit of some fine minds whom you're

02:36:11.160 --> 02:36:17.560
[Guest]: conversing with all the time I mean I became a life member of the PUCL at 15 years because my

02:36:17.560 --> 02:36:24.120
[Guest]: father paid the cheque for it and because he knew I was passionate about civil liberties so you know

02:36:24.120 --> 02:36:29.080
[Guest]: all of this is getting imbibed at various levels and you're writing you're writing by hand so I

02:36:29.080 --> 02:36:36.040
[Guest]: have my notes my essays my diary notes my letters to people and of course always encouraged by my

02:36:36.040 --> 02:36:42.200
[Guest]: mother to write letters to grandparents and others so writing and communicating was always

02:36:42.200 --> 02:36:47.160
[Guest]: important you know I mean the gift was not important but the letter was important and I was

02:36:47.160 --> 02:36:51.640
[Guest]: writing even before the JLT I was writing a lot at least once or twice a year I'd write long

02:36:51.640 --> 02:36:57.240
[Guest]: handwritten letters to close friends and family whom I felt like saying something to but after

02:36:57.240 --> 02:37:01.320
[Guest]: this experience I want to do it much more because now I feel it has to be something that has to

02:37:01.320 --> 02:37:06.360
[Guest]: become part of your life again it cannot be just something that you do to just say thank you for

02:37:06.360 --> 02:37:13.240
[Guest]: those letters but to try and continue because it is an important exercise to get some nice handmade

02:37:13.240 --> 02:37:19.960
[Guest]: paper from Chimanalaz to think of that letter pad write it out or recycle paper from an

02:37:19.960 --> 02:37:26.200
[Guest]: organization that does recycling work and and write it because I think it's that communication

02:37:26.200 --> 02:37:31.880
[Guest]: that receipt the receiving of that letter is so important and there's an old family friend of

02:37:31.880 --> 02:37:37.640
[Guest]: ours who lives in San Francisco and she half her half her time is spent in and that family is also

02:37:37.640 --> 02:37:43.000
[Guest]: in my very important part of my upbringing was my my mother's best school friend was Preeti Desai

02:37:43.000 --> 02:37:49.800
[Guest]: and her three sisters Jyoti, Sita and Bindu and one brother were like family to her and my father

02:37:49.800 --> 02:37:54.680
[Guest]: so we lots of holidays together and Bindu was Preeti and Bindu were like my political mentors

02:37:55.800 --> 02:38:01.320
[Guest]: cuttings about Palestine and cuttings about resistance in South Latin America South America

02:38:01.320 --> 02:38:05.080
[Guest]: all of that would come from the Guardian and the time that they would get and they would send it to

02:38:05.080 --> 02:38:13.640
[Guest]: me to read these we've lost the others but Sita's are there but Bindu is so much part of my life

02:38:13.640 --> 02:38:20.680
[Guest]: still she I got maybe five ten postcards from her in jail and she wrote to many of her academic and

02:38:20.680 --> 02:38:25.720
[Guest]: doctor friends all over the world who then wrote to me when I was inside so you know there's so

02:38:25.720 --> 02:38:32.200
[Guest]: much of this which is so important and continues to be important and why is it important only

02:38:32.200 --> 02:38:37.320
[Guest]: because you feel important at that moment or you feel loved no I think through every postcard that

02:38:37.320 --> 02:38:42.680
[Guest]: you get or letter that you get there is an idea there's a thought we are making a connection

02:38:43.480 --> 02:38:48.200
[Guest]: so Dilip D'Souza when he writes to you will be writing about his visit to Portugal where he saw

02:38:48.200 --> 02:38:52.440
[Guest]: that particular monument where he's which is writing about in the postcard that makes you

02:38:52.440 --> 02:38:56.280
[Guest]: reflect on that then you think of Mario Miranda and his postcard you know there's so many things

02:38:56.280 --> 02:39:02.520
[Guest]: that happen to you when you are reading and writing letters and the first letter I got in

02:39:02.520 --> 02:39:10.040
[Guest]: jail was on 27th of July and that was in an envelope and it was from Son Badra it was from

02:39:10.040 --> 02:39:17.080
[Guest]: the Adivasi union leaders women leaders Rajkumari and eight nine others had Angutha chapped it and

02:39:17.080 --> 02:39:24.040
[Guest]: they had written out this letter and it the my fellow inmates in the barrack six were saying

02:39:24.040 --> 02:39:28.760
[Guest]: what are all these letters why are you getting so many so then I would tell them about the women

02:39:28.760 --> 02:39:33.960
[Guest]: who have written them who's Rajkumari and who's Sukalo so about for an hour that conversation

02:39:33.960 --> 02:39:38.760
[Guest]: would take place till interest would wane I said no these are amazingly fantastic women you would

02:39:38.760 --> 02:39:43.240
[Guest]: never meet such women in your life they live in this thing they're fighting for their land and

02:39:43.240 --> 02:39:48.920
[Guest]: this thing writes they've been in jail twice I've been jailed only the first time so you know all

02:39:48.920 --> 02:39:56.840
[Guest]: these comparisons analogies become extremely important I don't know what it meant to my

02:39:57.480 --> 02:40:01.880
[Guest]: fellow inmates in barrack six but those conversations were very important to me to have

02:40:01.880 --> 02:40:10.440
[Amit Varma]: with them. Wow that's so fascinating another sort of strand I want to kind of pick up on where you

02:40:10.440 --> 02:40:15.960
[Amit Varma]: mentioned how it meant a lot to you to be living by the sea that you know you would have that sense

02:40:15.960 --> 02:40:21.400
[Amit Varma]: of calm and all of that and you've also spoken about times where you know you just like to be

02:40:21.400 --> 02:40:28.200
[Amit Varma]: yourself cooking or be with yourself doing something with your hands and one thing I

02:40:28.200 --> 02:40:33.160
[Amit Varma]: wonder then is that how in one's life especially if someone is as engaged with the world as you

02:40:33.160 --> 02:40:37.720
[Amit Varma]: are where you're always busy doing something organizing something speaking to people you know

02:40:37.720 --> 02:40:44.680
[Amit Varma]: how do you manage to make space for that heraav in your life like sometimes you know you just want to

02:40:45.720 --> 02:40:51.480
[Amit Varma]: sit back and sink into yourself and just find a moment of calm where your monkey mind is quiet

02:40:51.480 --> 02:40:57.160
[Amit Varma]: so to say and at the same time you have so many things to do which are not unpleasant things

02:40:57.160 --> 02:41:01.800
[Amit Varma]: to do you're passionate about it you wake up looking forward to doing them how have you kind

02:41:01.800 --> 02:41:08.280
[Amit Varma]: of managed that because you know what someone like me will know of you from the outside is someone

02:41:08.280 --> 02:41:14.520
[Amit Varma]: who's always involved and you know in your activism in your writing all of that but there is also a

02:41:14.520 --> 02:41:20.360
[Amit Varma]: private self sometimes you just want to chill sometimes you just want to blank mind look how

02:41:20.360 --> 02:41:25.080
[Amit Varma]: do you how do you manage these is it frustrating sometimes where there's just too much I never have

02:41:25.080 --> 02:41:30.040
[Guest]: enough time in the day it's like horrible it's horrible I'm always fighting and I think I'm

02:41:30.040 --> 02:41:36.440
[Guest]: driving everybody berserk with it because I'm trying to cram in maybe 40 things to do in a day

02:41:36.440 --> 02:41:41.800
[Guest]: when I can only do 10 and it's like very very tough and ask my family they go berserk with me

02:41:41.800 --> 02:41:46.280
[Guest]: because I make they they've seen this they've grown up with this so it must have been very

02:41:46.280 --> 02:41:54.120
[Guest]: tough for them but yeah but I do zealously try to grab my private moments and then my family

02:41:54.120 --> 02:42:00.600
[Guest]: tries to make me grab them too so that I try and get them but the holidays unfortunately have become

02:42:00.600 --> 02:42:05.480
[Guest]: less than they ought to be the earlier we used to be very very this thing about having family

02:42:05.480 --> 02:42:10.440
[Guest]: holidays three weeks a year three weeks in a year whatever but they have lessened a lot so

02:42:10.440 --> 02:42:15.720
[Guest]: those are kind of big big sacrifices that one has had to make in the last seven eight nine years

02:42:17.000 --> 02:42:21.560
[Guest]: hopefully that will change one keeps telling oneself that one needs to get that to change

02:42:21.560 --> 02:42:25.960
[Guest]: because I don't think those three weeks are going to make a difference but but it's tough

02:42:26.680 --> 02:42:31.400
[Guest]: so one just it's a tussle with oneself and as you kind of tell oneself about health also look after

02:42:31.400 --> 02:42:39.080
[Guest]: yourself all those things are a battle and I think my family has paid a price for this frenetic level

02:42:39.080 --> 02:42:47.240
[Guest]: of activity but I also feel that one is lucky to at least have the space and the place that one can

02:42:47.240 --> 02:42:52.520
[Guest]: sit up and sit one never had the pressures of not having a home or having to pay a loan for the home

02:42:52.520 --> 02:42:57.560
[Guest]: and I think I always recognize that that you know one is lucky activist in that sense and at least

02:42:57.560 --> 02:43:05.560
[Guest]: this fallback cushion was there and maybe that's why one can do more or should do more so you

02:43:05.560 --> 02:43:09.880
[Amit Varma]: mentioned how you know you decided you wanted to be a journalist when you read all the president's

02:43:09.880 --> 02:43:14.840
[Amit Varma]: men and then you know you got into college and you threw yourself into student politics you

02:43:14.840 --> 02:43:20.120
[Amit Varma]: protested free rise you were active in debating you were part of the film society all of that

02:43:20.120 --> 02:43:25.720
[Amit Varma]: tell me a little bit about what was your developing conception of yourself like when I think of myself

02:43:25.720 --> 02:43:30.760
[Amit Varma]: in college I mean I would have no way of answering that question because everything was a confused

02:43:30.760 --> 02:43:37.080
[Amit Varma]: hazy mess and you're just kind of going with the flow and whatever but in your case you know there

02:43:37.080 --> 02:43:45.240
[Amit Varma]: seems to be more purpose to kind of what you're doing so what was that period like like were you

02:43:45.240 --> 02:43:49.320
[Amit Varma]: so clear that you're going to be a journalist that this is just like a waiting period graduation

02:43:49.960 --> 02:43:56.760
[Guest]: get the degree and then I think college for me was a flowering of my personality so I think that

02:43:56.760 --> 02:44:01.080
[Guest]: journalism would have come later I was not looking at that state I was just enjoying every moment of

02:44:01.080 --> 02:44:08.280
[Guest]: that thing of a kind of an educational space and institution where you were challenged by the

02:44:08.280 --> 02:44:12.920
[Guest]: curriculum but not enough not to do lots of extracurricular stuff political engagement

02:44:12.920 --> 02:44:17.080
[Guest]: because those are the times when campuses were political and I think that's one of the

02:44:17.080 --> 02:44:21.960
[Guest]: linking up to your earlier question I think one of the reasons why you have this hopeless

02:44:21.960 --> 02:44:27.960
[Guest]: depoliticization of the middle class is the this whole lindow committee business not having

02:44:27.960 --> 02:44:33.320
[Guest]: elections in colleges and a completely depoliticization of the campus because I think

02:44:33.320 --> 02:44:38.280
[Guest]: the only politics that happens in campuses is ultra-right politics and that's that's really sad

02:44:38.280 --> 02:44:44.600
[Guest]: it's really really sad because there's a whole crop of us generations who got politicized on

02:44:44.600 --> 02:44:50.680
[Guest]: campus because that's the age right you're out of school you're on your own your mind is growing

02:44:50.680 --> 02:44:58.120
[Guest]: you're you're experimenting breaking away from what your family has stood for all of that is natural

02:44:58.680 --> 02:45:03.800
[Guest]: and I think that was so important to me Elfie years Elphinstone years were like really important

02:45:03.800 --> 02:45:09.240
[Guest]: for my formation in terms of what I became afterwards and what the these the the work

02:45:09.240 --> 02:45:17.640
[Guest]: I did afterwards and my engagement with student politics issues I mean I mean we saw so many

02:45:17.640 --> 02:45:21.960
[Guest]: lovely I mean I wish I could see the films that I saw there number of films I seen I can't see them

02:45:21.960 --> 02:45:27.800
[Guest]: I don't have the time but we saw the most glorious films I mean apart from really good solid classics

02:45:27.800 --> 02:45:34.840
[Guest]: and art films we saw I mean we saw three films a week in theaters you know and we bunk classes but

02:45:34.840 --> 02:45:40.760
[Guest]: we were very active on the campus and we had very good professors so they knew their tutorials would

02:45:40.760 --> 02:45:47.480
[Guest]: be submitted but not always we attended in class it was a fantastic atmosphere and I think we

02:45:47.480 --> 02:45:53.800
[Guest]: really need to fight to get our campuses back to a space in a stage by which really good politics

02:45:53.800 --> 02:46:00.760
[Guest]: can happen where the politics of equality and non-discrimination can be arenas in the campus

02:46:00.760 --> 02:46:05.240
[Guest]: because where else can you learn this you know imagine I mean I'm coming out of Manikji Cooper

02:46:05.240 --> 02:46:11.960
[Guest]: school and I'm going to Elphinstone and I'm engaging with the this whole question of feed

02:46:11.960 --> 02:46:16.280
[Guest]: eyes and of course but I'm also telling the political organization that is talking about

02:46:16.280 --> 02:46:23.160
[Guest]: feed eyes that please also raise the question of English language privilege because I'm already got

02:46:23.160 --> 02:46:29.800
[Guest]: a 20 point handicap over somebody who studied in the non-English languages because I can I can sail

02:46:29.800 --> 02:46:35.160
[Guest]: through my 11th and 12th without even opening my textbook if I'm not interested in getting 90 percent

02:46:35.160 --> 02:46:40.360
[Guest]: I can get at least 50 60 70 percent because of the wretched English language privilege so let's also

02:46:40.360 --> 02:46:45.720
[Guest]: battle for some sort of handicap marks for those persons who are not coming from you know so all

02:46:45.720 --> 02:46:51.640
[Guest]: those issues get crystallized if you are able to articulate them in that kind of space how many

02:46:51.640 --> 02:46:56.440
[Guest]: kids are given that in a commerce college today or in a science college today is there that kind

02:46:56.440 --> 02:47:03.720
[Guest]: of articulation possible we saw it during CA and NRC and we know the potential is there I mean the

02:47:03.720 --> 02:47:10.120
[Guest]: gathering we saw at August Kanti Maidan and then at Gateway for a deep politicized city like Bombay

02:47:10.120 --> 02:47:16.520
[Guest]: was tremendous so the potential among young people is always there but I think we need to also revive

02:47:16.520 --> 02:47:22.360
[Amit Varma]: politics on the campus to make this consistent. I guess you're saying this from you know an

02:47:22.360 --> 02:47:27.640
[Amit Varma]: Elphinstone upbringing point of view but the counterpoint to this would be so many campuses

02:47:27.640 --> 02:47:33.960
[Amit Varma]: in north and central India where you know politics just leads to violence and I guess the kind of

02:47:33.960 --> 02:47:37.960
[Amit Varma]: politics you have also depends on the kind of society you're in and the kind of people that

02:47:37.960 --> 02:47:42.440
[Guest]: there are you know those are not. See this is like a teacher telling me when we are doing teacher

02:47:42.440 --> 02:47:48.280
[Guest]: training on Koj and we say that Koj's principle is pedagogy multi-dimensional and we must bring

02:47:48.280 --> 02:47:52.840
[Guest]: conflictual issues into the classroom because to believe as an adult that the young mind has no

02:47:52.840 --> 02:47:58.200
[Guest]: capacity to deal with conflict is as an ageist prejudice you know so this is one of the discussions

02:47:58.200 --> 02:48:03.160
[Guest]: and trainings we have so many teachers say but you know you're talking about a very noisy classroom

02:48:03.160 --> 02:48:08.280
[Guest]: so I said yeah but it's the right kind of noise it's the noise that means questioning so to answer

02:48:08.280 --> 02:48:12.680
[Guest]: your question it's the kind of what kind of politics if you're talking about politics of the

02:48:12.680 --> 02:48:17.080
[Guest]: mob then obviously what you're saying is true that's why I said that the only politics left on

02:48:17.080 --> 02:48:22.440
[Guest]: the campus is right-wing politics but but if you're talking about the politics of organization

02:48:22.440 --> 02:48:27.160
[Guest]: the politics of constitutionalism the question of make deepening the constitution deepening

02:48:27.160 --> 02:48:31.800
[Guest]: democracy then this is the age to do it I mean you have to question your structures now and here

02:48:31.800 --> 02:48:37.640
[Guest]: now and learn how to do it and experiment with how to do it you might make mistakes but that's

02:48:37.640 --> 02:48:43.880
[Guest]: how you kind of get because I think to ensure that all our citizens forever remain politically

02:48:43.880 --> 02:48:50.680
[Guest]: active the campus is very important and we have to have politically actives I'm not talking about

02:48:50.680 --> 02:48:58.520
[Guest]: party politics but politically active citizenry is what strengthens democracy. So as we sort of

02:48:58.520 --> 02:49:03.320
[Amit Varma]: segue from your college years to actually joining journalism let me also ask you a larger question

02:49:03.320 --> 02:49:08.680
[Amit Varma]: about journalism which ties into your point about the importance of politics and political thinking

02:49:09.320 --> 02:49:15.640
[Amit Varma]: I did a recent episode with the journalist Samarth Bansal you know and one of the questions that we

02:49:15.640 --> 02:49:23.320
[Amit Varma]: sort of debated was just the meta question of what should a journalist report on because you know

02:49:23.320 --> 02:49:31.480
[Amit Varma]: a journalist or a publication can really write about anything but you choose to write about

02:49:31.480 --> 02:49:37.800
[Amit Varma]: some things and not about others and and that choice is aesthetic ethical political all of

02:49:37.800 --> 02:49:44.280
[Amit Varma]: these things everything kind of comes into it and this is something that I think increasingly we

02:49:44.280 --> 02:49:48.600
[Amit Varma]: need to think more about and you of course bemoaned and I share your lament of what is happening to

02:49:48.600 --> 02:49:57.480
[Amit Varma]: the media today and the spaces that they've vacated but on this larger question what has

02:49:57.480 --> 02:50:03.960
[Amit Varma]: been your evolving sense of it that if as a journalist you you have to think about what do

02:50:03.960 --> 02:50:09.720
[Amit Varma]: I write about you know or if as an editor you're saying what are the stories we will publish today

02:50:09.720 --> 02:50:17.400
[Amit Varma]: what will we put on page one and why you know what would your answer be today and how would

02:50:17.400 --> 02:50:22.360
[Amit Varma]: it have evolved over time and I understand that obviously there are nuances here like what is your

02:50:22.360 --> 02:50:27.560
[Amit Varma]: market or who are you speaking to and are you a tabloid or a broadsheet and obviously all of those

02:50:27.560 --> 02:50:35.240
[Amit Varma]: nuances are there but in general I think that you know there are many of us who are searching

02:50:35.240 --> 02:50:40.840
[Amit Varma]: for an answer to the question that goes beyond the functional one of what does the market want

02:50:40.840 --> 02:50:47.640
[Amit Varma]: what will sell most copies you know what is trending on twitter you know so is there so

02:50:47.640 --> 02:50:53.960
[Amit Varma]: how do you sort of look at this and how has your thinking on this evolved like where are you and

02:50:53.960 --> 02:50:59.320
[Guest]: how did you get here see I think as a practicing journalist I need to explain to all of you

02:50:59.320 --> 02:51:04.360
[Guest]: because you know you have probably not seen it from the inside I've been a practicing journalist

02:51:04.360 --> 02:51:08.760
[Guest]: as well but never mind no but I just want to say that I think what is often forgotten is that you

02:51:08.760 --> 02:51:15.320
[Guest]: know how is the whole concept of the fourth estate evolved I mean the fourth estate both internationally

02:51:15.320 --> 02:51:23.080
[Guest]: and nationally within India and South Asia it's evolved as an entity or a thing which is

02:51:23.080 --> 02:51:28.440
[Guest]: outside the state which is for which is by its very inherent nature anti-establishment and needs

02:51:28.440 --> 02:51:34.520
[Guest]: to question structures of state and society so you need the independence you need autonomy etc

02:51:34.520 --> 02:51:39.640
[Guest]: then as you evolve further and you get into a democratic setup you know you have this notion of

02:51:41.640 --> 02:51:49.240
[Guest]: ensuring that the journalist or the media and we begin with print then we move to electronic

02:51:49.240 --> 02:51:56.680
[Guest]: and digital should be equipped to question every governance structure that exists within that

02:51:56.680 --> 02:52:03.400
[Guest]: democracy right now having said that step back for a minute and look at the way our national

02:52:03.400 --> 02:52:08.840
[Guest]: movement and the freedom movement given what I was saying earlier where you have our best leaders

02:52:09.480 --> 02:52:16.680
[Guest]: and even the using media for political mobilization so Gandhi as an editor Gandhi as a writer but

02:52:16.680 --> 02:52:22.840
[Guest]: there's young India Harijan all the publications he edited Babasaheb Ambedkar edited like 15

02:52:22.840 --> 02:52:28.520
[Guest]: Mukhnayak so many of them so many of them and each one of them had a different stage and evolution

02:52:28.520 --> 02:52:35.880
[Guest]: so on the one hand I'm talking about the post independence what it ought to be or should be

02:52:36.440 --> 02:52:41.720
[Guest]: what it has become we'll come to later and what it has meant in terms of political emancipation I

02:52:41.720 --> 02:52:49.400
[Guest]: also flagged so it's very important to understand that the focus needs to always that of course the

02:52:49.400 --> 02:52:55.720
[Guest]: editorial in terms of comment and comment writing or feature writing is important but I think the

02:52:55.720 --> 02:53:03.160
[Guest]: journalists and publications and television channels and portals should never forget the

02:53:03.160 --> 02:53:10.600
[Guest]: primary duty is to report now reportage means what reportage means understanding the structure

02:53:10.600 --> 02:53:15.880
[Guest]: of society and state and having meticulous independent autonomous coverage of it okay

02:53:16.440 --> 02:53:23.160
[Guest]: so in traditional terms what this meant for us when we began was beat reporting okay beat reporting

02:53:23.160 --> 02:53:27.480
[Guest]: and what I would like to flag today is and I say this all the time because I take journalism

02:53:27.480 --> 02:53:35.080
[Guest]: classes also is I really bemoan the complete obfuscation and eradication of beat reporting

02:53:36.200 --> 02:53:42.280
[Guest]: today and I think this is very important so what am I saying here that you traditionally

02:53:42.280 --> 02:53:46.040
[Guest]: and there were lacunas there also it was not perfect so we'll come to that in a minute

02:53:46.040 --> 02:53:50.920
[Guest]: but what do I mean by I mean that how did we begin when we began as cub reporters or

02:53:50.920 --> 02:53:55.960
[Guest]: trainee reporter you begin with the crime beat then you go to the corporation beat then you

02:53:55.960 --> 02:54:02.040
[Guest]: I'm talking about cities then you go to the university beat then there's also health beat

02:54:02.040 --> 02:54:07.640
[Guest]: and then there's also science beat for the experts and there's also legal beat law beat

02:54:07.640 --> 02:54:11.400
[Guest]: court beat and there's of course the pinnacle which is everybody aspires to the political

02:54:11.400 --> 02:54:17.080
[Guest]: mantra elevator the vedan sudha beat or the parliament beat so these were the traditional

02:54:17.080 --> 02:54:21.640
[Guest]: I'm saying even then some of us were questioning like for instance we formed the women and media

02:54:21.640 --> 02:54:26.760
[Guest]: committee which I write about then there were the labor writers and all even then we would

02:54:26.760 --> 02:54:33.880
[Guest]: be moaning the fact that there was not enough attention paid to the labor beat workers issues

02:54:33.880 --> 02:54:39.240
[Guest]: agricultural beat no attention at all even that time or very little maybe sporadically when there

02:54:39.240 --> 02:54:44.760
[Guest]: was a drought but not as a big beat so farmers issues were not regularly covered agricultural

02:54:44.760 --> 02:54:50.200
[Guest]: issues were there was no environment and climate change was never really an issue you know so even

02:54:50.200 --> 02:54:55.560
[Guest]: then all this was being deepened and questioned but my point is that the beat journalism is gone

02:54:57.000 --> 02:55:02.200
[Guest]: never mind that those that didn't exist or were eroded didn't didn't exist even then you know

02:55:02.200 --> 02:55:06.760
[Guest]: so I think one of the things we really need to flag again today when we are looking at alternatives

02:55:06.760 --> 02:55:14.760
[Guest]: and your own experience Amit with this entire podcast is actually a reflection of this that

02:55:14.760 --> 02:55:19.640
[Guest]: to say that the market doesn't want it is bullshit you know I really whether it's with

02:55:19.640 --> 02:55:25.800
[Guest]: Bollywood and the kind of films being trashed out or whether it is media I don't buy that

02:55:25.800 --> 02:55:31.240
[Guest]: because who is deciding and who is giving we know the game of advertising what it was I mean it was

02:55:31.240 --> 02:55:35.320
[Guest]: it was all a bubble you told yourself that this is what worked and you told yourself this was the

02:55:35.320 --> 02:55:41.240
[Guest]: market wanted we know the world of TRPs where we know whether TRPs are represented or there

02:55:41.240 --> 02:55:45.800
[Guest]: enough critical studies on that so I think let's come back to the fact that who is honest enough

02:55:45.800 --> 02:55:51.480
[Guest]: to actually return to being a decent newspaper or a decent television channel or whatever and

02:55:51.480 --> 02:55:55.800
[Guest]: who is willing to back that financially because the issue really is ownership money and all of

02:55:55.800 --> 02:56:00.840
[Guest]: that which is what Vaya is trying to do that you know that funding by the viewer and all of that

02:56:00.840 --> 02:56:04.520
[Guest]: all experiments in the making we don't know if they're going to succeed in the long term

02:56:04.520 --> 02:56:08.840
[Guest]: scroll we just hope they do because if they don't then I think we are sunk because what little

02:56:08.840 --> 02:56:14.360
[Guest]: options we have will go so I think I'll return that I think there's looking at this entire

02:56:14.360 --> 02:56:21.720
[Guest]: business about number one reportage being as important as comment and when I mean by reportage

02:56:21.720 --> 02:56:27.480
[Guest]: I'm not about just individual fragmented stories but through those individual stories you're

02:56:27.480 --> 02:56:31.960
[Guest]: actually picking up trends you're picking up this thing and then you're doing an analysis

02:56:31.960 --> 02:56:36.440
[Guest]: so from the reportage comes the knowledge of analysis not just sitting in a editor's chair

02:56:36.440 --> 02:56:41.000
[Guest]: and doing the analysis with no knowledge of what's happening on the ground so today for instance and

02:56:41.000 --> 02:56:46.040
[Guest]: this is what I found so tragic and many of us were still involved with the Bombay Union of

02:56:46.040 --> 02:56:51.400
[Guest]: Journalists and the Delhi Union of Journalists is that you know 475 to 500 journalists lost their

02:56:51.400 --> 02:56:59.160
[Guest]: lives during COVID and it's not a national story just as you had nurses and Anganmadi workers and

02:56:59.160 --> 02:57:04.760
[Guest]: health workers who risked their lives so did journalists but it's not a story even for the

02:57:04.760 --> 02:57:11.240
[Guest]: media why would it be for politicians so you know I think this is where the huge disconnect lies

02:57:11.240 --> 02:57:16.120
[Guest]: that there are still journalists who want to do their job there's still journalists who are trying

02:57:16.120 --> 02:57:20.920
[Guest]: to do their job there's still journalists who are actually sacrificing lives for the job but they

02:57:20.920 --> 02:57:29.400
[Guest]: just don't get the visibility or the or the or the respect that they deserve maybe that was always

02:57:29.400 --> 02:57:34.360
[Guest]: the case but it is far more acute today so I'm just saying that you know so crisis reporting

02:57:34.360 --> 02:57:41.480
[Guest]: conflict reporting beat reporting and reporting before and no overemphasis on comment will itself

02:57:41.480 --> 02:57:48.440
[Guest]: sort of bring down the hysteria levels and the hate levels because I think facts speak stronger

02:57:48.440 --> 02:57:54.280
[Guest]: than words and many of the things that I'm talking about will actually the syncretism the

02:57:54.280 --> 02:58:00.120
[Guest]: lived secularism of people will also get reflected in those stories you know which is why there's a

02:58:00.120 --> 02:58:05.080
[Guest]: group of people in Tamil Nadu started this thing of My India or whatever they just report on all

02:58:05.080 --> 02:58:08.840
[Guest]: the good news stories because that's the other thing many of us used to feel as reporters that

02:58:08.840 --> 02:58:14.600
[Guest]: bad news is news but good news is no news you know so so much of this needs to be brought back

02:58:14.600 --> 02:58:20.680
[Guest]: to the debate obviously forms will change because media has changed so I'm not saying we go back in

02:58:20.680 --> 02:58:26.440
[Guest]: the in this go back four decades or three decades or two decades but we re-examine the proposition

02:58:26.440 --> 02:58:31.800
[Guest]: that are we doing justice to reportage and if reportage has to be engaged in fairly today

02:58:32.360 --> 02:58:39.240
[Guest]: of the various structures of governance how do we do it and if this is an age of shared news and

02:58:39.240 --> 02:58:44.840
[Guest]: syndication and shared platforms can this be done collectively I think these are some of the

02:58:44.840 --> 02:58:49.720
[Guest]: challenges that we need to do because the digital portals are trying it you know so you have a

02:58:49.720 --> 02:58:55.160
[Guest]: mukhnayak you have a wire you have very very interesting experiments you have a that Khabar

02:58:55.160 --> 02:59:01.080
[Guest]: Lahariya you have Gaon Ke Log many small and big interesting experiments taking place in the non

02:59:01.080 --> 02:59:09.640
[Guest]: in the non-english arena as well but this is no match for the kind of bombardment and this thing

02:59:09.640 --> 02:59:15.000
[Guest]: that we get from our electronic commercial channels I will I refuse to call them mainstream

02:59:15.000 --> 02:59:20.200
[Guest]: anymore they are commercial they're pure commerce so how does one counter this that is a huge

02:59:20.200 --> 02:59:24.600
[Guest]: challenge and of course some of our best journalistic minds are engaged in it but are they

02:59:24.600 --> 02:59:31.160
[Amit Varma]: enough you know so you know a couple of profound points which I want to underscore and the first

02:59:31.160 --> 02:59:36.600
[Amit Varma]: of them which might you know to the casual listener it might seem that hey what difference

02:59:36.600 --> 02:59:40.840
[Amit Varma]: does it make if there aren't beat if there isn't beat journalism but it's incredibly important and

02:59:40.840 --> 02:59:45.000
[Amit Varma]: I want to read out this passage from your book where you wrote about it where you wrote quote

02:59:45.000 --> 02:59:49.320
[Amit Varma]: I believe I was among the last generation of reporters to benefit from training on the beat

02:59:49.320 --> 02:59:53.640
[Amit Varma]: the loss of this structured framework has seminally reduced the quality and standards of

02:59:53.640 --> 02:59:58.680
[Amit Varma]: the profession we honed our skills as observers and critics of the system by talking to people

02:59:58.680 --> 03:00:03.400
[Amit Varma]: in the university in the municipal corporation the bmc beat in the mantra lay the seat of the

03:00:03.400 --> 03:00:07.960
[Amit Varma]: state government or in the courts we listen to court proceedings and debates in the assembly

03:00:07.960 --> 03:00:13.000
[Amit Varma]: to cover the courts to understand and report on the issues being contested meant plowing through

03:00:13.000 --> 03:00:18.360
[Amit Varma]: court records petitions and affidavit annexures it was not only about flippant oral comments made

03:00:18.360 --> 03:00:23.080
[Amit Varma]: in the courtroom each encounter allowed us to understand better the way these structures worked

03:00:23.080 --> 03:00:27.560
[Amit Varma]: in our democracy mundane beat reporting allowed us to pour through the agenda of the standing

03:00:27.560 --> 03:00:32.840
[Amit Varma]: committee meetings of the municipal council or to sense a pulse behind the assembly sessions

03:00:32.840 --> 03:00:38.440
[Amit Varma]: our exclusives our front pages had to be built on long hours of hectic consultations learning

03:00:38.440 --> 03:00:45.640
[Amit Varma]: and questioning stop quote and and the importance of this is that there is a deep engagement like

03:00:45.640 --> 03:00:49.720
[Amit Varma]: what I see happened like one of the things that has gone wrong with media today in addition to

03:00:49.720 --> 03:00:54.760
[Amit Varma]: many others but one of the things is that too many journalists today are generalists

03:00:55.400 --> 03:01:01.720
[Amit Varma]: right the new publications don't have budgets so you no longer have beats with dedicated reporters

03:01:01.720 --> 03:01:06.440
[Amit Varma]: one day you are reporting on bmc next day you're reporting from the hospital you're taking quotes

03:01:06.440 --> 03:01:11.320
[Amit Varma]: from people without getting quotes from five other people you are not questioning anything

03:01:11.320 --> 03:01:17.640
[Amit Varma]: it's it's become that kind of shallow reportage and the reason this matters is that I agree with

03:01:17.640 --> 03:01:24.120
[Amit Varma]: you that one of the functions of the media is to speak truth to power and to me the key word there

03:01:24.120 --> 03:01:28.760
[Amit Varma]: is truth right and how do you arrive at the truth you arrive at the truth by going as deep as

03:01:28.760 --> 03:01:34.600
[Amit Varma]: possible by gathering as many dots as you can so you you can build a sufficiently high definition

03:01:34.600 --> 03:01:39.960
[Amit Varma]: picture and again I say in truth to power the truth bit is important because it's also dangerous

03:01:39.960 --> 03:01:49.000
[Amit Varma]: to go in the other direction and you know become sort of become oppositional for the sake of it and

03:01:49.000 --> 03:01:56.680
[Amit Varma]: and we've seen that happening as well and the other profound point you made is about new ways of

03:01:56.680 --> 03:02:03.960
[Amit Varma]: perhaps collective reporting arising and I've been thinking a lot about in the creator economy

03:02:03.960 --> 03:02:09.640
[Amit Varma]: how new ways of expression are coming like I don't think there is any more any sense in any

03:02:09.640 --> 03:02:14.120
[Amit Varma]: of us hoping that the big publications are mainstream publications will deliver they're

03:02:14.120 --> 03:02:18.920
[Amit Varma]: not going to do that they have their pressures they have their incentives fine it is what it

03:02:18.920 --> 03:02:22.920
[Amit Varma]: is but we have the tools of production in our hand you know you mentioned my podcast listen

03:02:22.920 --> 03:02:26.760
[Amit Varma]: you know as an editor if I was I were to go to any mainstream house and say

03:02:28.600 --> 03:02:34.200
[Amit Varma]: I would be laughed out of the room right but there are so many people like me who don't have to

03:02:34.200 --> 03:02:40.600
[Amit Varma]: to conform to a particular conventional way of thinking who don't have to go through gatekeepers

03:02:40.600 --> 03:02:45.240
[Amit Varma]: and I think just as in the creator economy and really there's a thin line between creating and

03:02:45.240 --> 03:02:50.920
[Amit Varma]: reporting and all of this that I do see hope coming there you know the likes of Khabar Lahariya for

03:02:50.920 --> 03:02:55.720
[Guest]: example and so on absolutely that and I really feel that we should be talking on lines of this

03:02:55.720 --> 03:03:01.720
